(650, 8, '1: PHNOM PENH TO KAMPOT ', '<p>Transfer from Phnom Penh to Kampot (approximately 3 hrs) with your English speaking Tour Guide who will accompany you for the duration of your visit.</p>\n<p>The Charming town of Kampot is home to some of the best examples of French colonial architecture to be found in Cambodia today though many of the buildings are in need or repair. The riverside promenade is a favourite place for locals and tourists alike to stroll or just sit and take in the atmosphere. It is just a couple of kilometres to the Gulf of Thailand and late afternoon and early mornings you can see the fishing boats heading to fish overnight. Kampot is famous for its pepper, fish sauce and the huge durian fruit.</p>\n<p>After checking into your hotel take a relaxing walk around the town and the riverside and enjoy the laid back, friendly atmosphere. Enjoy the backdrop of the river and the Bokor Mountain dominating in the distance.</p>\n<p>Take a scenic river cruise on the Kampot River in the late afternoon. Sail past Cham Muslim villages, mangrove forests and atch the fishing boats heading out for their nightly catch. Enjoy the sun setting behind the Bokor Mountain before returning to Kampot town.</p>\n<p>The evening is free at leisure for you to stroll around the town. There are a variety of simple restaurants and your guide will be able to make some suggestions.</p>\n<p>Meal included:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; None</p>\n<p>Accommodation at: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <span lang="EN-AU">Selected hotel, Kampot</span></p>', 'southern-splendour-d1.jpg'),
(651, 8, '2: KAMPOT', '<p>(Optional tour &ndash; no extra charge &ndash; for the early starters: Walk the short distance from your hotel to the Kampot Fish Market. An early start of around 6 am is required to catch the fishing boats unload their catch. The fish and other seafood are quickly purchased and taken on to markets all over Cambodia. Tourists rarely visit this market but you need to go early &ndash; as it starts to get light there is little to see).</p>\n<p>Head out of Kampot this morning for Bokor National Park. The entrance to the park is a short 10km drive which is then followed by a drive 35km upwards as you climb the mountain. The road is one of the best in Cambodia and there are a few scenic viewpoints to stop and enjoy the sight of The Gulf of Thailand and across to Phu Quoc Island in neighbouring Vietnam.</p>\n<p>A hill station was founded here by the French in the 1920&rsquo;s. It was twice abandoned as battles raged and was one of the last holdouts of the Khmer Rouge regime. Visit the Catholic Church where the Khmer Rouge was holed up for several months. Another interesting stop is the Casino which is undergoing redevelopment. Enjoy the view over a sheer drop where it is said some of the big gamblers committed suicide after suffering losses at the casino&hellip;</p>\n<p>Descend a short distance and head to Popokvil Waterfalls, reached by a short walk. Keep your eyes out for giant red squirrels, monkeys or perhaps hornbills. Enjoy a picnic lunch at this scenic location. After it is time for the drive down the hill and back to Kampot town.</p>\n<p>Back in Kampot it is time for a massage with a difference &ndash; a &lsquo;seeing hands&rsquo; massage at the hands of a skilled blind masseur.</p>\n<p>The evening is free at leisure.</p>\n<p>Meal included:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Breakfast &amp; Picnic lunch</p>\n<p>Accommodation at: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <span lang="EN-AU">Selected hotel, Kampot</span></p>', 'southern-splendour-d2.jpg'),
(654, 8, '5: KEP TO PHNOM PENH', '<p>Enjoy a leisurely breakfast before the return drive to Phnom Penh (3 hrs).</p>\n<p>Alternatively your Asian adventures may continue onwards to Vietnam</p>\n<p>Meal included:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Breakfast</p>\n<p style="text-align: center;">&lt;End of services&gt;</p>', ''),
(1909, 5, '4: SIEM REAP', '<p><span lang="EN-US">This morning travel into the Cambodian countryside and out to the temple of Banteay Srei, dedicated to the Hindu god, Shiva. One of the most picturesque temples a morning visit provides a great opportunity to appreciate one of the most stunning achievements of Angkorian artisanship. </span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">In the afternoon travel to Tonle Sap Lake, the largest freshwater lake in Southeast Asia. The lake and its waters are the lifeblood of the country and millions of people depend on it. Officially a UNESCO Biosphere Reserve observing life on the lake makes for an interesting half day visit. Board a traditional wooden boat to visit one of the lesser-visited villages on the lake.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">On your return to Siem Reap stop at Artisan d&rsquo;Angkor, a project established to support Cambodian arts and crafts. </span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">This evening enjoy Dinner whilst watching a show of Apsara dancing, first performed in the Court of Kings at Angkor.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">After the show transfer back to your hotel.</span></p>\n<p>Meal included: Breakfast &amp; Dinner</p>\n<p>Accommodation at: <span lang="EN-AU">Selected hotel, </span>Siem Reap</p>', 'cambodia-discoverer-d4.jpg'),
(1910, 5, '5: SIEM REAP - DEPARTURE ', '<p>Transfer to the airport for your departure flight. &lsquo;Chum reap lear&rsquo; and goodbye to the Kingdom of Wonder.</p>\n<p>Meal included: Breakfast</p>\n<p>Accommodation at:&nbsp;<span lang="EN-AU">Selected hotel, </span>Siem Reap</p>\n<p style="text-align: center;">&lt;End of services&gt;</p>', ''),
(1907, 5, '2: PHNOM PENH - SIEM REAP ', '<p><span lang="EN-US">After breakfast transfer to the airport for the short flight to Siem Reap (45 mins). Upon arrival at Siem Reap airport you will be met by our local English speaking Tour Guide and transferred the short distance to your hotel to check in.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">In the afternoon begin your exploration of the Angkorian temples by visiting the ancient city of Angkor Thom which holds many important monuments which you will visit including the Bayon Temple located in the exact centre, the Baphoun, Terrace of the Elephants and Terrace of the Leper King.</span><span lang="EN-US">&nbsp; &nbsp;</span></p>\n<p>Meal included: Breakfast</p>\n<p>Accommodation at: <span lang="EN-AU">Selected hotel, </span>Siem Reap</p>', 'cambodia-discoverer-d2.jpg'),
(1908, 5, '3: SIEM REAP', '<p><span lang="EN-US">This morning continue your exploration of the Temples of Angkor by visiting Angkor Wat, the largest religious building in the world. Take your time to look at some of the more than 3,000 Apsara or &lsquo;heavenly maidens&rsquo; carvings, all of which are different. </span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">In the afternoon take a remork (similar to the Thai tuk tuk) to visit Ta Som, which features a memorable sacred fig tree strangling one of the entrance gates and Neak Poan accessed along a long wooden bridge. Continue to Ta Prohm, a unique temple that has been left to nature with trees and vines growing amongst the structures. This is one of the most photogenic temples in the Angkor area and recently gained fame as the &lsquo;Tomb Raider&rsquo; temple after featuring in the Angelina Jolie movie.</span></p>\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"><span lang="EN-US">This evening enjoy some modern Khmer theatre at a performance of Phare, the Cambodian Circus by professional artists from Phare Ponleu Selpak. Enjoy an hour long show which is a great, positive example of modern Cambodia and mixes theatre, dance, music, juggling and contortion.&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p>Meal included: Breakfast</p>\n<p>Accommodation at:&nbsp;<span lang="EN-AU">Selected hotel, </span>Siem Reap</p>', 'cambodia-discoverer-d3.jpg'),
(1906, 5, '1: ARRIVAL PHNOM PENH', '<p><span lang="EN-US">Upon arrival at Phnom Penh airport you will be met by our local English speaking Tour Guide and transferred to your hotel to check in.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Phnom Penh was known as the &lsquo;Pearl of Asia&rsquo; and like much of Cambodia was a vibrant and culturally developed city until the 1960&rsquo;s. Suffering at the hands of the Khmer Rouge the city was once evacuated by Pol Pot&rsquo;s army and became a ghost town. Today&rsquo;s Cambodia is a city on the move and one of the most interesting cities in Asia.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">This afternoon begin your tour of the Phnom Penh by visiting The Royal Palace. Built in 1866 today the palace is home to King Norodom Sihamoni who has ruled Cambodia since October 2004. Continue to the National Museum, home to a collection of Khmer sculpture including many of the original pieces from the Angkorian temples. </span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">After it is time to visit a bustling market and one of the most beautiful buildings in Cambodia, if not Asia. Central Market or Psar Thmei was originally constructed in 1937 following plans of the French architect, Louis Chauchon.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">In the evening enjoy dinner with great views over the river.</span></p>\n<p>Meal included: Dinner</p>\n<p>Accommodation at:&nbsp;<span lang="EN-AU">Selected hotel, Phnom Penh</span></p>', 'cambodia-discoverer-d1.jpg'),
(653, 8, '4: KEP', '<p>After breakfast head to the famous Kep Crab Market. A very calm place you can see crab and other seafood being sold, cooked and eaten at the market. The crabs are kept in baskets in the shallow waters along the shore and if a market trader or local restaurateur arrives the baskets are pulled in and discussion begins on the quality and price. Busiest at weekends and public holidays there is also activity on weekdays.</p>\n<p>Drive to the pier to catch a private local boat across to Koh Tonsai or Rabbit Island as it is also known. On arrival at Rabbit Island you can choose to walk around the perimeter (about 2 hrs walk) or just sit, relax and enjoy the beach and warm waters. Snorkeling gear is at your disposal if required.</p>\n<p>A seafood BBQ will be prepared for your lunch and some further time to relax.</p>\n<p>Mid-afternoon return by boat to the mainland and transfer the short distance back to your hotel.</p>\n<p>The evening is at leisure.</p>\n<p>Meal included:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Breakfast &amp; lunch</p>\n<p>Accommodation at: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <span lang="EN-AU">Selected hotel, Kep</span></p>', 'southern-splendour-d4.jpg'),
(652, 8, '3: KAMPOT TO KEP', '<p>A scenic journey awaits today for the drive to Kep. Set off mid-morning and drive via the little known, Secret Lake until you reach Starling Pepper Farm. Now it is time to learn about the famous Kampot pepper. First documented by Chinese explorers in the 1920&rsquo;s the Kampot pepper became famous in the 1800&rsquo;s as far away as Paris. On arrival take a tour of the pepper plantation and learn about the difference between the green, black, white and red peppercorns. Then it will time for a tasty lunch at the Starling Restaurant which will naturally include a few fresh green peppercorns.</p>\n<p>After lunch it is a short drive on to Kep which used to be a thriving seaside town in the 1960&rsquo;s. Designed for the rich Khmer with huge colonial villas, mansions and royal residences, the town fell apart and suffered huge demand under the Khmer Rouge. Today the town is revitalized as tourists once more visit Kep-sur-Mer as the French called it. A small local beach, delicious seafood and an easily accessible national park are just some of the highlights of Kep.</p>\n<p>Check in to your hotel and take some time to relax. The rest of the day is at leisure though your guide is on hand if you wish to take a tour of the town. Sunsets are particularly stunning and the Sailing Club or restaurants next to the Crab Market are greats venues for a sundowner whilst watching the sun setting.</p>\n<p>Meal included:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Breakfast &amp; lunch</p>\n<p>Accommodation at: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <span lang="EN-AU">Selected hotel, Kep</span></p>', 'southern-splendour-d3.jpg'),
(1320, 9, '5: RATANAKIRI', '<p>A full day is spent once again to learn about the minority peoples of Ratanakiri province and also to take in some delightful countryside.</p>\n<p>Leaving Banlung in a northwesterly direction today cross bamboo forests before reaching the village of Voen Sai located on a bank of the Tonle San river. Visit a Chinese enclave where Khmer is hardly spoken.</p>\n<p>Upstream of the Tonle San is Kaoh Peak, a village of the Kachok minority that practices funeral statuary or totems. Next pass through through rubber plantations to the waterfall of Chha Ong, where the river flows through the jungle before falling 30m into a gorge. It is possible to climb under the waterfall to a ledge behind the falling water.</p>\n<p>On the way back to Banlung stop at Boeng Yeak Lom, a beautiful blue, perfectly round, crater lake surrounded by forest. The clear waters are inviting and it is time for a relaxing late afternoon swim. From here it is back to Banlung and your lodge for the night.</p>\n<p>Dinner will be served at the lodge.</p>\n<p>Meal included:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Breakfast, Lunch and Dinner</p>\n<p>Accommodation at: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Selected hotel, Ratanakiri</p>', 'mekongsunset-d5.jpg'),
(1321, 9, '6: RATANAKIRI - PHNOM PENH OR SIEM REAP', '<p>This morning you can make a short visit to the local market. After it is time for the full day&rsquo;s drive to either Phnom Penh or Siem Reap with a lunch stop on the way. Arrive at your destination in the late afternoon/early evening.</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;" align="center">Meal included:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Breakfast and Lunch</p>\n<p style="text-align: center;" align="center">&nbsp;<span lang="EN-AU">&lt;End of services&gt;</span></p>', ''),
(1318, 9, '3: KRATIE - RATANAKIRI', '<p>Depart Koh Trong this morning and return to the mainland. An exciting morning awaits.</p>\n<p>Drive the short distance outside of Kratie to the starting point for a local boat cruise in search of the rare Irawaddy dolphins. These creatures spend most of their time in &lsquo;dolphin pools&rsquo; or certain stretches of the Mekong River. Spottings are frequent. Once your boatman spots the dolphins he will switch off the motor so you can watch them coming to the surface. The dolphin trips usually last around 1&frac12; hrs and are part of a community initiative to provide employment for the boatmen and also to protect the animals.</p>\n<p>Continue to the largest pagoda in Cambodia, Wat Sorsor Moi Roi or 100 Columns Temple. In fact there are 108 columns to be seen and also a few pillars from the old wooden temple that was built almost 500 years ago. Within the temple grounds visit the Mekong Turtle Conservation Project, set up to increase the wild population of the endangered Cantor&rsquo;s Softshell Turtle in the nearby Mekong River, through turtle hatchlings from a community-led turtle nest programme. &nbsp; The centre also has as a large outdoor pond for the turtle breeding program where you can view the larger adult Cantor&rsquo;s Softshell Turtles and also many other Asian turtle species. All entry fees will directly support this project and the participating local villagers in this unique conservation project.</p>\n<p>After enjoy your packed lunch within the ground of the pagoda. Then continue on the drive to Ratanakiri province. Travel time will be about 4hrs depending on the road condition.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Arrive in Banlung and check in at your hotel. Dinner will be served at the lodge.</p>\n<p>Meal included:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Breakfast, Lunch and Dinner</p>\n<p>Accommodation at: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Selected hotel, Ratanakiri</p>', 'mekongsunset-d3.jpg'),
(1319, 9, '4: RATANAKIRI', '<p>Spend the full day exploring the beauty of Ratanakiri.</p>\n<p>In the morning head northwards, almost to Laos and the village of Taveng. Cross the volcanic lava field of Veyrum Plang. Travelling north the landscape changes bit by bit from primary forest to cleared forest, bamboo and bush. Later on, stop at some Kreung villages located in the forest on both sides of the road. Learn about the minority tribe who have a centuries old tradition of erecting bachelor houses standing on long poles. These houses will remain until the young man achieves his goal and finds a wife. The unusual bachelor pad will then be destroyed before being raised again by younger men the following year. Enjoy some trekking through the forest and fields and possibly wading up a little river before reaching another Kreung village. From here it is back to Banlung and your lodge for the night.</p>\n<p>Dinner will be served at the lodge.</p>\n<p>Meal included:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Breakfast, Lunch and Dinner</p>\n<p>Accommodation at: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Selected hotel, Ratanakiri</p>', 'mekongsunset-d4.jpg'),
(1316, 9, '1: PHNOM PENH - KRATIE', '<p>Transfer from Phnom Penh to Kompong Cham (2 hrs) with your English speaking Tour Guide who will accompany you for the duration of your visit. Kompong Cham is a slow paced provincial capital set on the banks of the Mekong River. The town is dominated by the impressive Kizuna Bridge that spans the Mekong and was a gift from the Japanese.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>A short distance outside of Kompong Cham visit Wat Hanchey, offering excellent views over the Mekong River and beyond. Drive to the top (or if you prefer a short, steep walk) and visit the pagoda which dates from the 8th century. &nbsp;Wat Hanchey was an important religious center during the pre-Angkor Chenla period. &nbsp;Spread over the hilltop are various ruins including an ancient brick structure with Sanskrit inscriptions on the doorway and also some more unusual modern statues of large fruit and animals! There are usually a few young monks studying who you can speak to you if you like.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Close to town is Wat Nokor, an 11th century temple built of black sandstone and laterite and one of the last built under King Jayavarman VII. Adjacent is a modern temple with a completely different architectural style where a different form of Buddhism is preached.</p>\n<p>Stop for lunch at Smile Restaurant in Kompong Cham, which serves as a training centre for orphans and vulnerable children. The non-profit caf&eacute; is run by the Cambodian NGO, Buddhism for Social Development Action (BDSA).</p>\n<p>Continue along the Mekong passing many old wooden houses and Cham villages on the way to Kratie (2hrs). The Cham originated from Champa, a 7th century kingdom that was located in what is today central and southern Vietnam and lasted until 1832, before being conquered and annexed. Today the Cham can be found living mostly along the banks of the Mekong and Tonle Sap Rivers and may number as many as 500,000 in Cambodia making them the largest minority religion in the country.</p>\n<p>Arrive into Kratie, a town located on the Mekong with a distinctly French feel to it with some colonial buildings still remaining. The riverfront is the place to watch the action, be that life on the river or street markets that begin there. &nbsp;Take a boat across the Mekong to the island of Koh Trong&nbsp;<span lang="EN-US"><em>(Note: may be shared with other passengers)</em>&nbsp;</span>which will be your home for the next 2 nights. Arrive at Rajabori Villas and check in to your hotel.</p>\n<p>With luck you will have the opportunity to catch a memorable sunset. The Mekong River sunsets are some of the best you can see in the region and a suitable venue is located only a few minutes from your lodge.</p>\n<p>Dinner this evening at the lodge.</p>\n<p>Meal included:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Lunch and Dinner</p>\n<p>Accommodation at: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Selected hotel, Kratie</p>', 'mekongsunset-d1.jpg'),
(1317, 9, '2: KRATIE', '<p>Today is your chance to experience life on a Mekong River island. The island of Koh Trong is a friendly place and great for walking, jogging, cycling and just relaxing.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>In the mid-morning you will be collected by horse cart for a ride along the island trails to the local pagoda. A local community project offers you the chance to plant a tree and leave a positive trace on the island for years to come. After continue by horse cart to a local homestay where a traditional Khmer meal will be served.</p>\n<p>Return to the hotel where you will have free time for the rest of the day. Bicycles are available for house guests so you can explore the island on your own accord. Or you may prefer to relax at the swimming pool.</p>\n<p>This evening dinner will be served at the lodge.</p>\n<p>Meal included:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Breakfast, Lunch and Dinner</p>\n<p>Accommodation at: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Selected hotel, Kratie</p>', 'mekongsunset-d2.jpg'),
(1979, 6, '4: SIEM REAP - DEPARTURE', '<p>Transfer to the airport for your departure flight. &lsquo;Chum reap lear&rsquo; and goodbye to the Kingdom of Wonder.</p>\n<p>Meal included:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Breakfast</p>', ''),
(1978, 6, '3: SIEM REAP', '<p><span lang="EN-US">In the morning travel into the Cambodian countryside and out to the temple of Banteay Srei, one of the most picturesque temples. </span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">In the afternoon travel to Tonle Sap Lake, the largest freshwater lake in Southeast Asia. Board a traditional wooden boat to visit one of the lesser visited villages on the lake.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">On your return to Siem Reap stop at Artisan d&rsquo;Angkor, a project established to support Cambodian arts and crafts. Visit the workshop and see stone carvings, wooden sculptures, lacquer work and painting all being produced.</span></p>\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"><span lang="EN-US">This evening enjoy some modern Khmer theatre at a performance of Phare, the Cambodian Circus by professional artists from Phare Ponleu Selpak. Originally a project set up in refugee camps as a way to encourage young people to express themselves using art, the Phare circus is slowly becoming a worldwide name and a good example of responsible tourism that has been a success story.&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p>Meal included:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Breakfast</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;">Accommodation at: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <span lang="EN-AU">Selected hotel, </span>Siem Reap</p>', 'ancient-angkor-d3.jpg'),
(1976, 6, '1: ARRIVAL SIEM REAP', '<p><span lang="EN-US">Arrive at Siem Reap airport and meet your Tour Guide.&nbsp; Transfer to your hotel to check in.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">In the visiting Angkor Wat, the largest religious building in the world. </span> <span lang="EN-US">&nbsp;Take your time to look at some of the more than 3,000 Apsara or &lsquo;heavenly maidens&rsquo; carvings, all of which are different. The late afternoon light provides the best opportunity to observe and photograph the Apsaras.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Enjoy sunset at Angkor Wat with a cold coconut juice to cool down after your exciting exploration.</span></p>\n<p style="text-align: left;">Accommodation at: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <span lang="EN-AU">Selected hotel, </span>Siem Reap</p>', 'ancient-angkor-d1.jpg'),
(1977, 6, '2: SIEM REAP', '<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"><span lang="EN-US">After an early breakfast visit the ancient city of Angkor Thom by remork (the Cambodian equivalent of the Thai &lsquo;tuk tuk&rsquo;). Surrounded by walls with a height of 8m and length of 12km, the city was the last capital of the Khmer Empire. </span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Take a break around lunchtime back at your hotel.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">In the afternoon travel to Ta Som temple, which features a memorable sacred fig tree and then on to Preah Khan, built by King Jayavarman VII as a monastic and teaching complex.</span><span lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">The last stop of the day is at Ta Prohm, a unique temple that has been left to nature with trees and vines growing amongst the structures. This is one of the most photogenic temples in the Angkor area and recently gained fame as the &lsquo;Tomb Raider&rsquo; temple after featuring in the Angelina Jolie movie.</span><span lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Enjoy Dinner whilst watching a show of Apsara dancing, first performed in the court of kings at Angkor.</span></p>\n<p style="text-align: left;">Meal included:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Breakfast &amp; Dinner</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;">Accommodation at: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <span lang="EN-AU">Selected hotel, </span>Siem Reap</p>', 'ancient-angkor-d2.jpg');
