ent 5"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="50" Name="List Table 5 Dark Accent 5"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="51"\n   Name="List Table 6 Colorful Accent 5"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="52"\n   Name="List Table 7 Colorful Accent 5"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="46"\n   Name="List Table 1 Light Accent 6"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="47" Name="List Table 2 Accent 6"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="48" Name="List Table 3 Accent 6"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="49" Name="List Table 4 Accent 6"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="50" Name="List Table 5 Dark Accent 6"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="51"\n   Name="List Table 6 Colorful Accent 6"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="52"\n   Name="List Table 7 Colorful Accent 6"/>\n </w:LatentStyles>\n</xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 10]>\n<style>\n /* Style Definitions */\n table.MsoNormalTable\n	{mso-style-name:"Table Normal";\n	mso-tstyle-rowband-size:0;\n	mso-tstyle-colband-size:0;\n	mso-style-noshow:yes;\n	mso-style-priority:99;\n	mso-style-parent:"";\n	mso-padding-alt:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;\n	mso-para-margin:0in;\n	mso-para-margin-bottom:.0001pt;\n	mso-pagination:widow-orphan;\n	font-size:10.0pt;\n	font-family:"Times New Roman","serif";}\n</style>\n<![endif]--></p>\n<p align="center"><span lang="EN-AU">&lt;End of services&gt;</span></p>', 'BTB3.png'),
(1821, 17, '9', '<p><span lang="EN-US">This morning take the shared boat transfer out of 4 Rivers. Meet your driver and guide who will then accompany you on the road transfer to Sihanoukville (approximately 4hrs). </span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">On arrival in Sihanoukville check in to your hotel. The afternoon is then at leisure for you to enjoy some beach and relaxation time.</span></p>', 'D9_edit.jpg'),
(1822, 17, '10', '<p><span lang="EN-US">The day is at leisure with optional island trips.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">(Optional: Swim &amp; Snorkel &ndash; Three Islands Tour -&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">Take a full day trip on a wooden boat to explore three different islands off Sihanoukville with the chance to swim and snorkel.&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">Set sail from the dock at Sihanoukville and cross to the island of Koh Chaluh to see beautiful corals and colourful fish &ndash; enjoy some snorkeling time (equipment provided). Next it is on to Koh Russei or Bamboo Island where there is more coral and swimming opportunities. On the beach enjoy a seafood BBQ with dr</span><span lang="EN-US">inks and fruit. The final stop is either Koh Tres for snorkeling or Koh Takiev. You can let the captain know at the start of the day which is most of interest. Return to Sihanoukville in the late afternoon).</span></p>', 'D10_edit.jpg'),
(1823, 17, '11', '<p><span lang="EN-US">The day is at leisure with optional island trips.</span></p>\n<div>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">(Optional: Be a local on Koh Rong Island -&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">Combine some leisure time with some real village activities on Koh Rong Island. Begin the day by taking the hour long FastCat ferry across to the island.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Experience some home grown, one-on-one experiential activities with village guides playing a pivotal role - making you feel genuinely welcome, relaxed and ready to jump in and immerse yourself in somevery relevant local experiences - guided walk to Soksan waterfalls with an orientation of the village community areas and plantations; sling fishing from the wharf with the expert local kids, learning the art of rowing a woven basket, taking village made polystyrene skiffs on a river or&nbsp;a foreshore expedition. Beachcombers will love to walk the fine white coral sand and exotic sea shells. Water babies can revel in emerald clear water and those lost in thought will gaze out across a shimmering sea alive with shoals of baitfish. Lunch is a feast of fresh caught seafood, salads and fruits. </span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">After a fun and experiential day take the fast ferry back to depart mid-afternoon arriving around 4.30pm back in Sihanoukville).</span></p>\n</div>', 'D11_edit.jpg'),
(1824, 17, '12', '<p><span lang="EN-US">Enjoy a leisurely morning to enjoy the beach before the early afternoon drive to Phnom Penh city or airport (4hrs). Alternatively your Cambodian adventures may continue by heading east to Kampot and Kep.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">&lsquo;Chum reap lear&rsquo; and goodbye to the Kingdom of Wonder.</span></p>', ''),
(2031, 22, '5: SIEM REAP (DEPARTURE DAY)', '<p><span lang="EN-US">Transfer to the airport for your departure flight. &lsquo;Chum reap lear&rsquo; and goodbye to the Kingdom of Wonder.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Meal included:</span><span lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">Breakfast&nbsp;</span></p>', ''),
(2027, 22, '1: ARRIVAL SIEM REAP', '<p><span lang="EN-US">Upon arrival at Siem Reap airport this morning you will be met by our local English speaking Tour Guide and transferred the short distance to your hotel to check in.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">This afternoon travel by car for a course inspection of the route you will be running on Sunday. Depending on your interests and time the inspection will be either a simple drive around or can be slower to incorporate some temple and countryside visits along the way.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Reach the finishing point of the marathon opposite Angkor Wat and enjoy sunset with a cold coconut juice to cool down.</span><span lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Meal included:&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">None&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Accommodation at:</span><span lang="EN-US">&nbsp;Selected hotel, Siem Reap&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 11.0pt; font-family: ''Comic Sans MS'';">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</span></p>', 'Moat_of_Angkor_Thom.jpg'),
(2028, 22, '2: SIEM REAP', '<p><span lang="EN-US">Travel this morning to Ta Prohm, a unique temple that has been left to nature with trees and vines growing amongst the structures. Enjoy walking along the sandy paths and under huge banyan trees as you explore this 12th century temple. </span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Travel back into Siem Reap and your guide will assist you in collecting the race kit (badge, free t-shirt and time chip) at the hotel chosen for the registration.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">The rest of the day is at leisure to allow you to prepare for an early start and the morning race. We recommend dinner at your hotel and perhaps a plate of pasta to build up your carbohydrates for the race. </span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Meal included:&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">Breakfast</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Accommodation at:</span><span lang="EN-US">&nbsp;Selected hotel, Siem Reap&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>', 'Ta_Prohm_Tomb_Raider_temple.jpg'),
(2029, 22, '3: SIEM REAP (RACE DAY)', '<p><span lang="EN-US">An early start today depending on your chosen race:</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">42km Full Marathon &ndash; start at 4.30 a.m.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">21km Half Marathon &ndash; start at 6.00 a.m.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Your guide will meet you this morning at the hotel (one hour before starting time) as you travel by remork (the Khmer equivalent of the Thai tuk tuk) out to the starting point of the race.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Do your last warming up exercises and then it is a case of testing your stamina and endurance as you run around the race course, passing many temples as you go. The start and finish point is at Angkor Wat. Whilst the course is completely flat the temperature can be the biggest hindrance for runners not acclimatized to warmer temperatures. However water, energy drinks, snacks are provided at regular intervals throughout the race.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Highlights of the race are passing Takeo, Sra Srang, Ta Prohm, Prasat Kravan, through two gates of Angkor Thom, passing the Bayon Temple and finishing on the home stretch in front of Angkor Wat.&nbsp;</span>After reaching the finishing point collect your medal and cool down with sugar cane juice and water.</p>\n<p>A 1 hour body massage has been arranged at the hotel spa for you this afternoon.</p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">In the evening enjoy Dinner whilst watching a show of Apsara dancing, first performed in the court of kings at Angkor. A set menu of Khmer cuisine will be served as you enjoy the show.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Meal included: </span><span lang="EN-US">Breakfast/Dinner</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Accommodation at:</span><span lang="EN-US">&nbsp;Selected hotel, Siem Reap</span><span lang="EN-US">&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>', 'Run_the_marathon_amongst_temples.jpg'),
(2030, 22, '4: SIEM REAP (RECOVERY DAY)', '<p><span lang="EN-US">This morning continue your exploration of the Temples of Angkor by visiting Angkor Wat, the largest religious building in the world. Take your time to look at some of the more than 3,000 Apsara or &lsquo;heavenly maidens&rsquo; carvings, all of which are different.&nbsp;</span>Continue to the ancient city of Angkor Thom. Five huge gates with huge stone faces provide access. Angkor Thom holds many important monuments including the Bayon Temple located in the exact centre, the Baphoun, Terrace of the Elephants and Terrace of the Leper King. Of course many of these you would have seen from the race course on the previous day.</p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Return to the hotel after midday to enjoy an afternoon at leisure. &nbsp;</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">This evening enjoy some modern Khmer theatre at a performance of Phare, the Cambodian Circus by professional artists from Phare Ponleu Selpak. Originally a project set up in refugee camps as a way to encourage young people to express themselves using art, the Phare circus is slowly becoming a worldwide name and a good example of responsible tourism that has been a success story. Enjoy an hour long show which is a great, positive example of modern Cambodia and mixes theatre, dance, music, juggling and contortion.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Meal included: </span><span lang="EN-US">Breakfast</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Accommodation at:</span><span lang="EN-US">&nbsp;Selected hotel, Siem Reap</span><span lang="EN-US">&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>', 'Historic_Angkor_Wat.jpg'),
(1857, 3, '1: ARRIVAL PHNOM PENH', '<!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>\n <o:OfficeDocumentSettings>\n  <o:TargetScreenSize>800x600</o:TargetScreenSize>\n </o:OfficeDocumentSettings>\n</xml><![endif]-->\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Upon arrival at Phnom Penh airport you will be met by our local English speaking Tour Guide and transferred to your hotel to check in &nbsp;</span></p>\n<div>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">This afternoon begin your tour of the Phnom Penh by visiting The Royal Palace. Wander through the complex, gardens and visit the interesting Silver Pagoda which houses a collection of Buddha statues, one of which is decorated with 9,584 diamonds and also take a look at the floor which is covered by 5,000 silver tiles.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Continue to the National Museum, home to a collection of Khmer sculpture including many of the original pieces from the Angkorian temples. </span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">After it is time to visit a bustling market and one of the most beautiful buildings in Cambodia, if not Asia. Central Market or Psar Thmei was originally constructed in 1937 following plans of the French architect, Louis Chauchon.</span><span lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">In the evening take dinner at a classic venue, the legendary FCC or Foreign Correspondents&rsquo; Club, located in a colonial building on the Riverside.&nbsp;</span></p>\n</div>\n<p>Meal included:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Dinner</p>\n<p>Accommodation at: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <span lang="EN-AU">Selected hotel, Phnom Penh</span></p>', 'D1-edit.jpg');
