(2016, 20, '13: SIEM REAP - DEPARTURE', '<p>The time is at leisure to enjoy Siem Reap under your own accord until the time of your departure transfer.</p>\n<p>Transfer to the airport for your departure flight. &lsquo;Chum reap lear&rsquo; and goodbye to the Kingdom of Wonder.</p>\n<p><em>The itinerary above as shown is for High Water cruises along the river. The Low Water itinerary varies &ndash; please contact us for details. As with all river cruises in the world the itinerary is subject to change according to water levels, weather and other factors.</em></p>', ''),
(2015, 20, '12: SIEM REAP', '<p>This morning travel into the Cambodian countryside and out to the temple of Banteay Srei, dedicated to the Hindu god, Shiva. Before reaching the temple <span lang="EN-US">visit the Landmine Museum located near Banteay Srei.&nbsp; The museum was founded by Mr Aki Ra who was once a child soldier for the Khmer Rouge before changing allegiance to work as a de-miner for first the Cambodian Army and later the United Nations. Aki Ra won an award from CNN as one of their Top 10 Heroes in 2010. Along with his Cambodian Self Help Demining group they have helped clear about 50,000 mines and weapons, many of which can be seen at the museum today.</span></p>\n<p>Continue to Banteay Srei, one of the most picturesque temples where a morning visit provides a great opportunity to appreciate one of the most stunning achievements of Angkorian artisanship. Small in size the carvings are exquisite at one of the best preserved temples in Cambodia. Banteay Srei is different to the other temples as it is constructed of pink sandstone and the name means &lsquo;Citadel of the Women&rsquo;.</p>\n<p>Following the visit head to Golden Silk Pheach Farm is located 7km from the Banteay Srei temple and is an excellent example of an NGO that preserves traditional arts in a sustainable way that provides employment to local villagers in a poor part of Siem Reap province. More than 100 employees work to produce fine textiles using the rare golden silk with methods that have been handed down through the owners family. The work is extremely detailed, can take months to complete and many of the final pieces cost thousands of dollars. A visit is highly recommended for those who appreciate fine artisanship and Khmer culture. A tour of the silk farm lasts about one hour.</p>\n<p>After the visit return to your hotel where the afternoon is at leisure.</p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">In the evening enjoy dinner at one of Siem Reap&rsquo;s most popular restaurants, Cuisine Wat Damnak. The restaurant is owned by the author of &lsquo;Cambodian Cooking&rsquo;, Joann&egrave;s Rivi&egrave;re. There is no a la carte menu at Wat Damnak, instead a set menu that changes weekly to incorporate as many fresh and seasonal ingredients as possible. Dining is a real exploration of modern Khmer cuisine. </span><em><span lang="EN-US">(Note &ndash; Cuisine Wat Damnak is closed from mid-Aug to mid-Oct and every Sun &amp; Mon. If your visit coincides with these dates we will either reschedule for another night of your stay or propose a meal at another excellent local restaurant).</span></em></p>', 'Golden_Silk_Farm.jpg'),
(2014, 20, '11: SIEM REAP', '<p>This morning begin your exploration of the Temples of Angkor by visiting Angkor Wat, the largest religious building in the world. Built by Suryavarman II in the early 12th century as a state temple and later mausoleum, Angkor Wat was originally a Hindu complex to honour Vishnu, the Hindu God.</p>\n<p>Angkor Wat is unlike other temples in that it is orientated towards the west, typically the direction of death. A magnificent moat surrounds the temple on all sides with a long causeway providing access. An alternative eastern entrance is the best way to start a morning tour and avoid the crowds. Take your time to look at some of the more than 3,000 Apsara or &lsquo;heavenly maidens&rsquo; carvings, all of which are different.</p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">After continue to visit the ancient city of Angkor Thom. Surrounded by walls with a height of 8m and length of 12km, the city was the last capital of the Khmer Empire. Five huge gates with huge stone faces provide access. Angkor Thom holds many important monuments which you will visit including the Bayon Temple located in the exact centre, Terrace of the Elephants and Terrace of the Leper King.&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Take a break around midday back at your hotel.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">In the mid-afternoon </span>take a remork (similar to the Thai tuk tuk) to Ta Prohm, a unique temple that has been left to nature with trees and vines growing amongst the structures. This is one of the most photogenic temples in the Angkor area and recently gained fame as the &lsquo;Tomb Raider&rsquo; temple after featuring in the Angelina Jolie movie. Enjoy walking along the sandy paths and under huge banyan trees as you explore this 12th century temple.</p>\n<p>Return to your hotel to freshen up.</p>\n<p>This evening enjoy some modern Khmer theatre at a performance of Phare, the Cambodian Circus by professional artists from Phare Ponleu Selpak. Originally a project set up in refugee camps as a way to encourage young people to express themselves using art, the Phare circus is slowly becoming a worldwide name and a good example of responsible tourism that has been a success story. Tours have visited France, Germany and the UK already. Enjoy an hour long show which is a great, positive example of modern Cambodia and mixes theatre, dance, music, juggling and contortion (Note &ndash; your seats are in category A, which means the best seats in the house for watching and acoustics and also includes a special gift).</p>\n<p>Once the show has finished return to your hotel.</p>', 'Angkor_Wat_UNESCO_World_Heritage_Site.jpg'),
(2013, 20, '10: ARRIVAL SIEM REAP', '<p>This may be the last day but the cruising adventure is far from over as you head off by skiff after breakfast into the 22,000-hectare Prek Toal Core Bird Reserve on Tonle Sap Lake, one of the largest freshwater bodies in Asia and the last refuge in Southeast Asia for large waterbirds like the spot-billed pelicans, milky stork, black-headed ibis and the elusive masked finfoot. Along the way, visit floating houses and fish farms, and learn about sustainable development initiatives like Saray, a cooperative of women who weave water hyacinth into 100% organic mats and home accessories for some of Southeast Asia&rsquo;s finest hotels. Visitors are invited to test our knotting skills, usually to the amusement of the resident experts.</p>\n<p>Return to the Aqua Mekong to pack up and then disembark for the road journey to Siem Reap. The drop off point is at Park Hyatt Siem Reap where you will be staying the next 3 nights.</p>\n<p>The rest of the day is at leisure before beginning your exploration of the Angkorian temples.</p>', 'Saray_Womens_Cooperative.jpg'),
(2012, 20, '9: CRUISING THE MEKONG', '<p>This morning continue exploring remote communities around the Tonle Sap River, an ecological hot spot designated as a UNESCO Biosphere Reserve in 1997. Today travel by skiff to the village of Chnok Tru, as photogenic as it is remote and thus completely self-sufficient.</p>\n<p>Here you will &ldquo;slide&rdquo; into an ice factory, the importance of which will be obvious after a few days in Southeast Asia. As local factory workers explain how they make and use the ice for fish preservation, our expert guides translate and get answers to your questions about this livelihood so different from ours. Also be on the lookout in this lake village for floating schools, riverside churches and pagoda, and even the karaoke bar and police station. Literally everything and everyone in Chnok Tru travels by small boat through the intricate network of canals crisscrossing this tiny town.</p>\n<p>Back on board the Aqua Mekong, cruise onward to the remote fishing village of Moat Kla.&nbsp; Climb back into the skiffs and head for the shore where your expert guides act as translators, allowing you to pose questions to the people of Moat Kla about their lives.</p>\n<p>You may be surprised to see that although most communities on the Tonle Sap are quite isolated, even Moat Kla has floating &lsquo;convenience&rsquo; stores stocked with fishing tackle, cooking utensils, rice, beer, candy, fruits and vegetables. Along the water, there are also small merchants like egg vendors, women selling bamboo stalks stuffed with sticky rice and even divers hired to search for lost objects.</p>\n<p>Moat Kla is the last village in Siem Reap Province on the southeastern end of the lake and only accessible by water. The community is largely of Vietnamese descent, owing to its settlement long before the nuances of international borders.</p>\n<p>Aqua Expeditions has made special arrangements for guests to attend the blessing ceremony conducted at Moat Kla&rsquo;s Buddhist temple, home to only four monks.</p>', 'Floating_Village_Tonle_Sap.jpg'),
(2010, 20, '7: CRUISING THE MEKONG', '<p>Shifting gears from the sleepy countryside to this country&rsquo;s political and economic capital, sail into Phnom Penh where Art Deco buildings still stand in the shadows of ever-rising skyscrapers and vintage cyclos cruise alongside imported European sports cars. Buddhist temples, French colonial villas and the Royal Palace provide photogenic backdrop to international business and a new generation of boutique hotels, chic shopping and cosmopolitan nightlife.</p>\n<p>Today&rsquo;s urban adventure by two wheel motorized tuk-tuks take in this historic city&rsquo;s most important sites including the 1866 Royal Palace that is still home to the reigning monarch and its Silver Pagoda, the royal compound&rsquo;s most famous attraction, so called because in 1962 then Prince Sihanouk ordered the floor inlaid with 5,329 genuine silver tiles. Today the pavilion houses many jewelled statues and images, including the 17th century Emerald Buddha, made of Baccarat crystal, and a life size gold Maitreya Buddha adorned 9,584 diamonds, the largest of which weighs 25 carats.</p>\n<p>Just next door, the National Museum of Cambodia houses the world&rsquo;s largest collection of Khmer art, much of it removed from Angkor Wat to prevent looting. Here we can linger among the linga, representations of the Hindu deity Shiva, and thousands of other artefacts including an imposing 11th century bronze sculpture of a reclining Vishnu that is considered a monumental example of Khmer statuary.</p>\n<p>Sip sun downers on the Observation Deck.</p>\n<p>In the evening enjoy a performance by renowned Cambodian apsara dancers who continue an ancient tradition venerated on the intricately carved walls at Angkor Wat.</p>', 'Royal_Palace_Phnom_Penh.jpg'),
(1459, 19, '16: KOH KONG - PHNOM PENH DEPARTURE', '<p class="MsoNormal"><span lang="EN-US">This morning take the shared boat transfer out of 4 Rivers. Meet your driver and guide who will take you back to Phnom Penh for a departure flight (4&frac12;-5 hours). Alternatively we can assist on transfers to Thailand (Bangkok is about 6 hours drive away).&nbsp;</span></p>', 'Cyclo_driver_Phnom_Penh.jpg'),
(1458, 19, '15: KOH KONG', '<p><span lang="EN-US">After a slow breakfast depart on a private tour to see the Tatai Waterfall. Taking the boat for about 45 minutes head into the heart of the Cardamom jungle&nbsp;until you reach the&nbsp;turbulent waters of the falls.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Depending on the season and water levels you can enjoy a natural hydromassage from the waters, kayak in the calmer waters and then enjoy a picnic lunch at the falls.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">In the mid-afternoon return by boat to the 4 Rivers Lodge for your overnight stay. </span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Dinner at the lodge.</span></p>', 'Unique_4_Rivers_Lodge.jpg'),
(1456, 19, '13: SIHANOUKVILLE', '<p class="MsoHeader" style="text-align: justify; text-justify: inter-ideograph;"><span lang="EN-US">The day is at leisure with optional island trips.</span></p>\n<p>(Optional Tour: Swim &amp; Snorkel - Three Islands Tour -&nbsp;Take a full day trip on a wooden boat to explore three different islands off Sihanoukville with the chance to swim and snorkel.&nbsp;<span lang="EN-US">Set sail from the dock at Sihanoukville and cross to the island of Koh Chaluh to see beautiful corals and colourful fish &ndash; enjoy some snorkeling time (equipment provided). Next it is on to Koh Russei or Bamboo Island where there is more coral and swimming opportunities. On the beach enjoy a seafood BBQ with drinks and fruit. The final stop is either Koh Tres for snorkeling or Koh Takiev. You can let the captain know at the start of the day which is most of interest. Return to Sihanoukville in the late afternoon).</span></p>', 'Sihanoukville_Island_Tour.jpg');
INSERT INTO `itinerary` (`id`, `tour_id`, `day`, `description`, `image`) VALUES
(1455, 19, '12: KAMPOT - SIHANOUKVILLE', '<p><span lang="EN-US"><em>(Optional tour &ndash; no extra charge &ndash; for the early starters: Walk the short distance from your hotel to the Kampot Fish Market. An early start of around 6 am is required to catch the fishing boats unload their catch. The fish and other seafood are quickly purchased and taken on to markets all over Cambodia. Tourists rarely visit this market but you need to go early &ndash; as it starts to get light there is little to see).</em></span></p>\n<p class="MsoHeader" style="text-align: justify; text-justify: inter-ideograph;"><span lang="EN-US">After breakfast it is time to say au revoir to sleepy Kampot and head on to the main beach destination of the country, Sihanoukville (travel time approximately 2 hours). Check in to your hotel and enjoy the rest of the day at leisure to enjoy the beach.</span></p>', 'Spectacular_Sunset_Sihanoukville.jpg'),
(1454, 19, '11: KAMPOT', '<p>The charming town of Kampot is home to some of the best examples of French colonial architecture to be found in Cambodia today though many of the buildings are in need of repair. The riverside promenade is a favourite place for locals and tourists alike to stroll or just sit and take in the atmosphere. It is just a couple of kilometres to the Gulf of Thailand and late afternoon and early mornings you can see the fishing boats heading to fish overnight. Kampot is famous for its pepper, fish sauce and the huge durian fruit.</p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">This morning enjoy</span><span lang="EN-US"> a relaxing walk around the town and the riverside and enjoy the laid back, friendly atmosphere. Enjoy the backdrop of the river and the Bokor Mountain dominating in the distance. Enjoy a massage with a difference &ndash; a &lsquo;seeing hands&rsquo; massage at the hands of a skilled blind masseur.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Take a scenic river cruise on the Kampot River in the late afternoon. Sail past Cham Muslim villages, mangrove forests and watch the fishing boats heading out for their nightly catch. Enjoy the sun setting behind the Bokor Mountain before returning to Kampot town.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">The evening is free at leisure for you to stroll around the town. There are a variety of simple restaurants and your guide will be able to make some suggestions.</span></p>', 'Kampot_Market.jpg'),
(1452, 19, '9: KEP', '<p><span lang="EN-US">Drive to the pier to catch a private local boat across to Koh Tonsai or Rabbit Island as it is also known. On arrival at Rabbit Island you can choose to walk around the perimeter (about 2 hrs walk) or just sit, relax and enjoy the beach and warm waters. Snorkeling gear is at your disposal if required.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">A seafood BBQ will be prepared for your lunch and some further time to relax.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Mid-afternoon return by boat to the mainland and transfer the short distance back to your hotel.</span></p>', 'Excursion_Rabbit_Island.jpg'),
(1453, 19, '10: KEP - KAMPOT', '<p><span lang="EN-US">The journey on to your next destination takes you into the countryside once more</span><span lang="EN-US">. Set off mid-morning and drive via the little known, Secret Lake until you reach Starling Pepper Farm. Now it is time to learn about the famous Kampot pepper. First documented by Chinese explorers in the 1920&rsquo;s the Kampot pepper became famous in the 1800&rsquo;s as far away as Paris. On arrival take a tour of the pepper plantation and learn about the difference between the green, black, white and red peppercorns. Then it will time for a tasty lunch at the Starling Restaurant which will naturally include a few fresh green peppercorns.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Following lunch head further into the countryside and to the cave of Phnom Chhnork. Your journey takes you through rice paddies in one of the most scenic parts of Cambodia with the backdrop of limestone hills. Steps lead you into the cave where has the aura of a church and is home to a 7th century brick temple.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Continue on your way to Kampot to arrive in the afternoon.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">The evening is at leisure.</span></p>', 'Kampot_Fishing_Boat.jpg'),
(1451, 19, '8: PHNOM PENH - KEP', '<p><span lang="EN-US">After breakfast leave your hotel for the journey to Cambodia&rsquo;s southern coast (travel time around 3 hrs not including stops) and the town of Kep which</span><span lang="EN-US"> used to be a thriving seaside town in the 1960&rsquo;s. Designed for the rich Khmer with huge colonial villas, mansions and royal residences, the town fell apart and suffered huge demand under the Khmer Rouge. Today the town is revitalized as tourists once more visit Kep-sur-mer as the French called it. A small local beach, delicious seafood and an easily accessible national park are just some of the highlights of Kep.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US"><span lang="EN-US">On arrival in Kep head to the famous Crab Market. A very calm place you can see crab and other seafood being sold, cooked and eaten at the market. The crabs are kept in baskets in the shallow waters along the shore and if a market trader or local restaurateur arrives the baskets are pulled in and discussion begins on the quality and price. Busiest at weekends and public holidays there is also activity on weekdays. You can choose to stay for lunch at one of the many shacks serving delicious food or head to your hotel to relax.</span></span></p>\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; text-justify: inter-ideograph;"><span lang="EN-US">The rest of the day is at leisure though your guide is on hand if you wish to take a tour of the town. Sunsets are particularly stunning and the Sailing Club or restaurants next to the Crab Market are great venues for a sundowner whilst watching the sun setting.</span></p>', 'Kep_Crab_Market.jpg'),
(1457, 19, '14: SIHANOUKVILLE - KOH KONG', '<p><span lang="EN-US">Leave Sihanoukville after breakfast as you head into the Cardamom Mountains for a stay at one of Cambodia&rsquo;s most unique places, the 4 Rivers Floating Lodge in Koh Kong. The drive will take about 4 hours from where it is a short shared boat ride to your accommodation for the night.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">On arrival you can check into your floating tent and relax a little. The tents are permanently moored up on a quiet stretch of river with the backdrop of rainforest. You will really feel at one with nature in your new home.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Activities available include swimming in the river, trying your hand at kayaking, fishing or in the evening to see fireflies lighting up a tree. It is also possible to go on an optional sunset cruise (paid locally).</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Dinner at the lodge.</span></p>', 'Cardamom_Mountains_Pristine_Beauty.jpg'),
(1450, 19, '7: PHNOM PENH', '<p><span lang="EN-US">In the morning visit the Tuol Sleng Genocide Museum and the &lsquo;Killing Fields&rsquo; of Choeung Ek. During the Pol Pot regime, Toul Sleng, formerly a high school was converted to a detention centre known as S21. After interrogation and often torture, prisoners were transferred to &lsquo;Killing Fields&rsquo; where they were often tortured again and brutally killed.&nbsp; Choeung Ek was a Chinese Cemetery before it became the Khmer Rouge&rsquo;s best known Killing Field. The remains of almost 9,000 bodies have been excavated from mass graves in this area. Today Choeung Ek is a Memorial site for Cambodians and visitors from all over the world to pay their respects for those lost. A memorial stupa has been erected and displays over 5,000 human skulls, bones and clothes of the victims. During the Khmer Rouge years, thousands of Cambodians were tortured and imprisoned in detention centres around the country; the visit is a profoundly moving but also depressing experience. However the insight into the cruel Khmer Rouge regime is educational and part of understanding Khmer culture as it is today.</span>Return to Phnom Penh for lunch at a classic venue, the legendary FCC or Foreign Correspondents&rsquo; Club, located in a colonial building on the Riverside. Enjoy a set Khmer menu with great views over the river.</p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">This afternoon you will visit The Royal Palace, built in 1866 by King Norodom; the Palace is made up from a number of structures within a pagoda-style compound one of which is The Silver Pagoda. The Silver Pagoda takes its name from the 5,000+ silver tiles and the building itself holds a number of national treasures perhaps most notably are a life-sized gold Maitreya Buddha decorated with 9584 diamonds, weighing in a at 90 kg and a small 17th century Emerald Buddha made from baccarat crystal.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Continue to visit the National Museum, a Khmer temple inspired building that houses the world&rsquo;s largest collection of Khmer art sculptures, ceramics and bronzes from different periods of Cambodian history. Over 5,000 objects are on display including Angkorian era statues, lingas and other artifacts, most notably the legendary statue of the &lsquo;Leper King.&rsquo; Though the emphasis is on Angkorian artifacts, there is also a good collection of pieces from later periods, including a special exhibition of post-Angkorian Buddha figures.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">After a chance to freshen up back at the hotel a relaxing evening is planned with a dinner cruise along the Mekong and Tonle Sap rivers. With views of the popular Phnom Penh riverside and the Phnom Penh skyline this is the chance to take it easy at the end of the day with some fresh air. Enjoy a tasty set menu served from the on-board kitchen by internationally trained chefs. A bar offers an extensive collection of beers, wines and cocktails.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Return to your hotel.</span></p>', 'Phnom_Penh_Heritage.jpg'),
(1449, 19, '6: BATTAMBANG - PHNOM PENH', '<p><span lang="EN-US">Depart from Battambang this morning for the drive to Phnom Penh (travel time around 6 hrs not including stops). A little outside of the town visit one of the best preserved temples around Battambang, Wat Banan is visited by climbing 358 stone steps to the top of a hill. Once a Buddhist temple, the origins of the temple are unclear though it could have been an inspiration for Angkor Wat to which it has many similarities. From the ruined temple there are nice views over the surrounding rice fields.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US"><span lang="EN-US">Further on the road to Phnom Penh, a short distance from the town of Kompong Chhnang, one reaches the scenic pottery village of Ondong Rossey. It seems that every house is involved in the industry and all over Cambodia ox-carts can be seen selling wares from the village. Ondong Rossey is very typical of a Cambodian village and the surrounding countryside is beautiful with rice fields dotted with sugar palm trees. Keep your eyes out in case one of the village men are climbing up bamboo ladders to take the rice wine or toddy from the trees. Enjoy a packed lunch in a quiet spot in the village.</span></span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Reach Phnom Penh in the late afternoon and check in to your hotel. Phnom Penh was known as the &lsquo;Pearl of Asia&rsquo; and like much of Cambodia was a vibrant and culturally developed city until the 1960&rsquo;s. Suffering at the hands of the Khmer Rouge the city was once evacuated by Pol Pot&rsquo;s army and became a ghost town. Today&rsquo;s Cambodia is a city on the move, still many years behind the development of neighbouring Vietnam or Thailand, though ever changing and one of the most interesting cities in Asia. </span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">The evening is at leisure.</span></p>', 'Pottery_Village.jpg'),
(1446, 19, '3: SIEM REAP', '<p><span lang="EN-US">This morning travel into the Cambodian countryside and out to the temple of Banteay Srei, dedicated to the Hindu god, Shiva. One of the most picturesque temples a morning visit provides a great opportunity to appreciate one of the most stunning achievements of Angkorian artisanship. Small in size the carvings are exquisite at one of the best preserved temples in Cambodia. Banteay Srei is different to the other temples as it is constructed of pink sandstone and the name means &lsquo;Citadel of the Women&rsquo;. </span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Visit the nearby Landmine Museum.&nbsp; The museum was founded by Mr Aki Ra who was once a child soldier for the Khmer Rouge before changing allegiance to work as a de-miner for first the Cambodian Army and later the United Nations. Aki Ra won an award from CNN as one of their Top 10 Heroes in 2010. Along with his Cambodian Self Help Demining group they have helped clear about 50,000 mines and weapons, many of which can be seen at the museum today.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">In the afternoon travel to Tonle Sap Lake, the largest freshwater lake in Southeast Asia. The lake and its waters are the lifeblood of the country and millions of people depend on it. Officially a UNESCO Biosphere Reserve observing life on the lake makes for an interesting half day visit. Board a traditional wooden boat to visit Kompong Khleang, one of the lesser visited villages on the lake.</span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; text-justify: inter-ideograph;"><span lang="EN-US">On your return to Siem Reap the evening is at leisure.</span></p>', 'Life_on_Tonle_Sap_Lake.jpg'),
(1447, 19, '4: SIEM REAP - BATTAMBANG', '<p><span lang="EN-US">Transfer from Siem Reap to Battambang (approximately 3 hrs) and check in to your hotel.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">This afternoon head 12km out of town to Phnom Sampeau. The limestone outcrop is home to a variety of temples and excellent views of the countryside dotted with palm trees and rice paddy fields. There is also a more sinister side as Phnom Sampeau is home to the Killing Caves, where Khmer Rouge executed prisoners. Many of them were thrown to the deaths through a skylight in the cave roof.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Stay until dusk to catch the natural phenomenon of thousands of bats exiting a cave. They fly one by one out of the cave creating patterns in the sky. It is quite a spectacular to behold.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Transfer back to Battambang and your hotel. The evening is at leisure.</span></p>', 'Village_Children.jpg'),
(1448, 19, '5: BATTAMBANG', '<p><span lang="EN-US">The morning is free and easy in Battambang and your guide will accompany according to your preferences. If you are interested in heritage then the streets of the town are ideal for taking a walk to see many of the old French style colonial buildings that are in a relatively good state of repair. A visit to the market can also give you a feel for Cambodian daily life. If your interest is more in the local villages then some time can be spent seeing the many different kinds of food prepared just outside of Battambang town. The fish paste (prahoc) is too smelly for most though more appetizing are the local fruits and fried bananas sold in the friendly villages. We suggest a visit to the ruins of an 11th century temple can be found at Wat Ek Phnom, with a surrounding active pagoda and lotus ponds adding to the atmospheric location. One of the most famous carvings, the Churning of the Ocean of Milk is similar to that seen at Angkor Wat.&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">In the afternoon try a fun activity again in the countryside surrounding the town. Travel a few kilometres to the start of one of the most fun &lsquo;train rides&rsquo; you will ever experience. The train or &lsquo;nori&rsquo; is consists of a wooden platform placed on 4 wheels and connected to a gasoline engine that powers the device. Used initially as a way of transporting goods between villages, today it is a popular way to transport tourists through the countryside with a little extra adrenalin added on a 12km trip.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Return to your hotel for the chance to freshen up before visiting a circus performance at the renowned Phare Ponleu Selpak. More in the style of Cirque du Soleil than a traditional European circus, be amazed for an hour by a show of modern Cambodian tales told through dance, acrobatics, aerial acts and music. The performers are all students at the Phare training centre in Battambang that provide a place for poor communities to express themselves in art. It has become so successful that the professional graduates perform nightly in Siem Reap and some schools have toured Europe, Japan and Australia. Besides the entertainment your visit helps sustain the project. <em>(Note: shows are held every Monday &amp; Thursday and occasionally on other days. Should your visit not coincide with one of these days then we will arrange a visit to Phare, Siem Reap instead).</em></span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">After the show it is off the Jaan Bai restaurant for dinner. This training and development restaurant is run by the Cambodian Children&rsquo;s Trust which is working to break the cycle of poverty in Battambang by empowering underprivileged children. Enjoy a healthy menu using seasonal organic produce with some of the best tastes from South East Asia combining with Western influences. Jaan Bai is set in a French colonial building in the heart of Battambang.</span></p>', 'Battambang_House.jpg'),
(1444, 19, '1: ARRIVAL SIEM REAP ', '<p><span lang="EN-US">Upon arrival at Siem Reap airport you will be met by our local English speaking Tour Guide and transferred the short distance to your hotel to check in.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US"><span lang="EN-US">In the afternoon visit the ancient city of Angkor Thom. Surrounded by walls with a height of 8m and length of 12km, the city was the last capital of the Khmer Empire. Five huge gates with huge stone faces provide access. Angkor Thom holds many important monuments which you will visit including the Bayon Temple located in the exact centre, the Baphoun, Terrace of the Elephants and Terrace of the Leper King.</span></span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">This evening enjoy a Welcome Dinner whilst watching a show of Apsara dancing, first performed in the court of kings at Angkor.</span></p>', 'Angkor_Thom_Gateway.jpg'),
(1445, 19, '2: SIEM REAP', '<p><span lang="EN-US">This morning continue your exploration of the Temples of Angkor by visiting Angkor Wat, the largest religious building in the world. Built by Suryavarman II in the early 12th century as a state temple and later mausoleum, Angkor Wat was originally a Hindu complex to honour Vishnu, the Hindu God.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Angkor Wat is unlike other temples in that it is orientated towards the west, typically the direction of death. A magnificent moat surrounds the temple on all sides with a long causeway providing access. An alternative eastern entrance is the best way to start a morning tour and avoid the crowds. Take your time to look at some of the more than 3,000 Apsara or &lsquo;heavenly maidens&rsquo; carvings, all of which are different.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Take a break around lunchtime back at your hotel.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">In the afternoon take a remork (similar to the Thai tuk tuk) to Ta Prohm, a unique temple that has been left to nature with trees and vines growing amongst the structures. This is one of the most photogenic temples in the Angkor area and recently gained fame as the &lsquo;Tomb Raider&rsquo; temple after featuring in the Angelina Jolie movie. Enjoy walking along the sandy paths and under huge banyan trees as you explore this 12th century temple.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Next visit Preah Khan built by King Jayavarman VII as a monastic and teaching complex. Unlike Ta Prohm much of the temple has been restored. Walk through the corridors and take time to appreciate the delicate carvings.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Continue to visit Ta Som, which features a memorable sacred fig tree strangling one of the entrance gates and Neak Poan accessed along a long wooden bridge.&nbsp;</span></p>', 'Angkor_Wat_UNESCO_World_Heritage_Site.jpg'),
(1937, 7, '4: SIEM REAP - DEPARTURE', '<p style="text-align: left;">Transfer to the airport for your departure flight. &lsquo;Chum reap lear&rsquo; and goodbye to the Kingdom of Wonder.</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;">Meal included: Breakfast</p>\n<p style="text-align: center;" align="center"><span lang="EN-AU">&nbsp;</span></p>', ''),
(1934, 7, '1: ARRIVAL SIEM REAP', '<p><span lang="EN-US">Upon arrival at Siem Reap airport this morning you will be met by our local English speaking Tour Guide and transferred the short distance to your hotel to Sofitel Angkor Phokeethra Golf &amp; Spa Resort to check in. </span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">This afternoon begin your exploration of the Temples of Angkor by visiting the ancient city of Angkor Thom including the Bayon Temple located in the exact centre. Continue to Angkor Wat, the largest religious building in the world. Built by Suryavarman II in the early 12th century as a state temple and later mausoleum, Angkor Wat was originally a Hindu complex to honour Vishnu, the Hindu God. The late afternoon light provides the best opportunity to observe and photograph the Apsaras.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">This evening enjoy a Welcome Dinner whilst watching show of Apsara dancing, first performed in the court of Kings at Angkor.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Meal included: </span><span lang="EN-US">Dinner &nbsp;</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Accommodation at:</span><span lang="EN-US"> Sofitel Angkor Phokeethra, Siem Reap&nbsp; </span><span lang="EN-US">&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>', 'golf-break-d1.jpg'),
(1935, 7, '2: SIEM REAP', '<p><span lang="EN-US">This morning transfer to Phokeethra Country Club for 18 holes of golf. A caddy and buggy are supplied. (Note: please bring your own footwear and golf clubs though both are available for hire if required).</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Enjoy your round of golf at Cambodia&rsquo;s first championship course. The 7,145 yard, 18-hole course was designed to be a challenge for amateurs and professionals &ndash; natural lagoons and sand traps will challenge you to up your game. Holes are a mixture of par 3s, 4s &amp; 5s.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">In the mid-afternoon travel to Ta Prohm by remork (similar to the Thai tuk tuk), a unique temple that has been left to nature with trees and vines growing amongst the structures. This is one of the most photogenic temples in the Angkor area and recently gained fame as the &lsquo;Tomb Raider&rsquo; temple after featuring in the Angelina Jolie movie.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Enjoy dinner at one of the very best restaurants serving traditional Khmer food, in a lush contemporary setting. Located on the Riverside the restaurant has a relaxing, tropical garden and smaller, indoor dining area. The menu will take you on an exploration of many recipes almost lost from the Kingdom.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Meal included: </span><span lang="EN-US">Breakfast/Dinner &nbsp; &nbsp;</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Accommodation at:&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">Sofitel Angkor Phokeethra, Siem Reap&nbsp;</span></p>', 'golf-break-d2.jpg');
