e 3 Accent 5"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="49" Name="List Table 4 Accent 5"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="50" Name="List Table 5 Dark Accent 5"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="51"\n   Name="List Table 6 Colorful Accent 5"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="52"\n   Name="List Table 7 Colorful Accent 5"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="46"\n   Name="List Table 1 Light Accent 6"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="47" Name="List Table 2 Accent 6"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="48" Name="List Table 3 Accent 6"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="49" Name="List Table 4 Accent 6"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="50" Name="List Table 5 Dark Accent 6"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="51"\n   Name="List Table 6 Colorful Accent 6"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="52"\n   Name="List Table 7 Colorful Accent 6"/>\n </w:LatentStyles>\n</xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 10]>\n<style>\n /* Style Definitions */\n table.MsoNormalTable\n	{mso-style-name:"Table Normal";\n	mso-tstyle-rowband-size:0;\n	mso-tstyle-colband-size:0;\n	mso-style-noshow:yes;\n	mso-style-priority:99;\n	mso-style-parent:"";\n	mso-padding-alt:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;\n	mso-para-margin:0in;\n	mso-para-margin-bottom:.0001pt;\n	mso-pagination:widow-orphan;\n	font-size:12.0pt;\n	font-family:"Cambria","serif";\n	mso-ascii-font-family:Cambria;\n	mso-ascii-theme-font:minor-latin;\n	mso-hansi-font-family:Cambria;\n	mso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin;\n	mso-bidi-language:AR-SA;}\n</style>\n<![endif]--></p>\n<p>A very special morning awaits you today. Leave the hotel at around 5am to experience sunrise at Ta Prohm &ndash; an atmospheric location that avoids the crowds often seen at Angkor Wat. The light will as the sun rises at this unique temple that has been left to nature with trees and vines growing amongst the structures. This is one of the most photogenic temples in the Angkor area and recently gained fame as the &lsquo;Tomb Raider&rsquo; temple after featuring in the Angelina Jolie movie. Enjoy walking along the sandy paths and under huge banyan trees as you explore this 12th century temple at daybreak.</p>\n<p>After having time to enjoy sunrise travel to Sra Srang, the royal bathing pool. Close by in the local village it is time for a local breakfast. A traditional Khmer wooden house is the setting for an energizing noodle breakfast containing rice noodles and a fish-based green curry gravy made from lemongrass, kaffir lime and turmeric. Fresh greens are served on top to make a very popular Khmer breakfast dish.</p>\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; text-justify: inter-ideograph;"><span lang="EN-US">Following your hearty breakfast the rest of the morning is &lsquo;free and easy&rsquo;. Your guide and driver can take you to see temples of the Grand Circuit such as Preah Khan and Ta Som or instead you can choose to visit Banteay Srei, &lsquo;Citadel of the Women&rsquo;. Or if you prefer a second visit to Angkor Wat can be arranged to see the temple in the morning light.</span></p>\n<p>Return to the hotel around midday where you will have the afternoon at leisure to relax. Take the time to have a swim at the hotel pool and recuperate some energy after the early start.</p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">In the early evening enjoy a pre-dinner aperitif of an infused rice wine called &lsquo;Sombai&rsquo; (meaning &lsquo;some rice please&rsquo; in the Khmer language). Local spices and fruits are blended together with rice liquor to create a delicious fusion. The Sombai workshop is located in a charming wooden house a few minutes drive from Siem Reap town. Beautifully hand-painted bottles make for an interesting souvenir if you wish to buy and bring back home for your loved ones&hellip;or for yourself as part of an extending tasting!</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Continue for dinner</span>&nbsp;at one of Siem Reap&rsquo;s most popular restaurants, Cuisine Wat Damnak. The restaurant is owned by the author of &lsquo;Cambodian Cooking&rsquo;, Joann&egrave;s Rivi&egrave;re. There is no a la carte menu at Wat Damnak, instead a set menu that changes weekly to incorporate as many fresh and seasonal ingredients as possible. Dining is a real exploration of modern Khmer cuisine. (Note &ndash; Cuisine Wat Damnak is closed from mid-Aug to mid-Oct and every Sun &amp; Mon. If your visit coincides with these dates we will either reschedule for another night of your stay or propose a meal at another excellent local restaurant).</p>', 'cambodia-cuisine-d4.jpg');
