ine;"><strong>Why not combine this Kep visit with our other culinary tours to Siem Reap and Phnom Penh? Please enquire for further details or see our &lsquo;Cambodia Culture &amp; Cuisine&rsquo; tour.</strong></span></p>\n</div>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', ''),
(1918, 14, '2: PHNOM PENH', '<p><span lang="EN-US">Khmer cuisine is not as well-known as that from Vietnam or Thailand though is equally as good. Fresh, seasonal fruits, vegetables and spice combine to make dishes less spicy than countries such as Laos or Thailand but rich in taste. This morning it is time to try your hand at Khmer cooking in a hands on interactive class.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">In the afternoon you will visit The Royal Palace, built in 1866 by King Norodom; the Palace is made up from a number of structures within a pagoda-style compound one of which is The Silver Pagoda. Continue to visit the National Museum, a Khmer temple inspired building that houses the world&rsquo;s largest collection of Khmer art sculptures, ceramics and bronzes from different periods of Cambodian history.&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">After it is time to visit a bustling market and one of the most beautiful buildings in Cambodia, if not Asia. Central Market or Psar Thmei.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">This evening dine at one of Cambodia&rsquo;s most famous restaurants and the best address in Phnom Penh to try Khmer cuisine. Try a traditional Khmer menu and enjoy some alfresco dining at its finest in Phnom Penh.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Meal included: </span><span lang="EN-US">Breakfast/Lunch/Dinner &nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span lang="EN-US">Accommodation at:</span><span lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">Selected hotel, Phnom Penh</span></p>', 'phnom-penh-cuisine-d2.jpg');
