e 3 Accent 5"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="49" Name="List Table 4 Accent 5"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="50" Name="List Table 5 Dark Accent 5"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="51"\n   Name="List Table 6 Colorful Accent 5"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="52"\n   Name="List Table 7 Colorful Accent 5"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="46"\n   Name="List Table 1 Light Accent 6"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="47" Name="List Table 2 Accent 6"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="48" Name="List Table 3 Accent 6"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="49" Name="List Table 4 Accent 6"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="50" Name="List Table 5 Dark Accent 6"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="51"\n   Name="List Table 6 Colorful Accent 6"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="52"\n   Name="List Table 7 Colorful Accent 6"/>\n </w:LatentStyles>\n</xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 10]>\n<style>\n /* Style Definitions */\n table.MsoNormalTable\n	{mso-style-name:"Table Normal";\n	mso-tstyle-rowband-size:0;\n	mso-tstyle-colband-size:0;\n	mso-style-noshow:yes;\n	mso-style-priority:99;\n	mso-style-parent:"";\n	mso-padding-alt:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;\n	mso-para-margin:0in;\n	mso-para-margin-bottom:.0001pt;\n	mso-pagination:widow-orphan;\n	font-size:12.0pt;\n	font-family:"Cambria","serif";\n	mso-ascii-font-family:Cambria;\n	mso-ascii-theme-font:minor-latin;\n	mso-hansi-font-family:Cambria;\n	mso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin;\n	mso-bidi-language:AR-SA;}\n</style>\n<![endif]--></p>\n<p>After breakfast leave Siem Reap and drive to the great Tonle Sap Lake, the largest fresh water lake in South East Asia and the heart of the Cambodian fishing industry and lifeblood for millions of Khmers living on and around it. A short instruction will be provided on kayaking before you paddle off. The guide will lead the way as you kayak amongst the Kampong Khleang village. This is a fascinating area to explore as only a small number of tourists make it out to this area. The houses are mostly built on stilts, up to 8m in height. In the dry season it is possible to drive in areas that 9 months of the year are under water.<span style="font-family: ''Comic Sans MS''; font-size: 11pt;"><br /></span></p>\n<p>Take a break at a local house where you will enjoy a packed lunch on the verandah of the stilted house. It is another opportunity to see the daily life of the villagers who adapt to changing water levels of the Tonle Sap.</p>\n<p>A boat will take you back to your starting point from where you will then cycle on through the countryside to the Roulos temples. Stop to visit Bakong Temple, the largest and most interesting of the three main temples, which is dedicated to the Hindu god, Shiva. It is said to be a representation of Mt Meru, the home of the gods and served as the first state temple of the Angkor period. The five tiered pyramid temple dominates and is surrounded by a moat and concentric walls. After return by vehicle to your hotel to finish an exciting and rewarding day.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The last evening is free for you to explore Siem Reap on your own accord. Perhaps visit Pub Street and have a drink or dinner to celebrate a few days of easy adventure.</p>\n<p>(Note: cycling distance approximately 25km on mostly flat tracks, sandy paths and small roads. There is time to stop for photos and the tour will last approximately 8 hrs including breaks and 1 hour of kayaking. The support vehicle and motorboat will act as back up if you need to stop and to avoid traffic entering/leaving Siem Reap. When the water level is low on Tonle Sap Lake kayaking will be arranged at an alternative village).<em><span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 11.0pt; font-family: ''Comic Sans MS''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''MS Mincho''; mso-fareast-theme-font: minor-fareast; mso-bidi-font-family: DaunPenh; mso-bidi-theme-font: minor-bidi; mso-ansi-language: EN-US; mso-fareast-language: EN-US; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA;"><br /></span></em></p>', 'BIKE-ANGKOR-D3.jpg'),
(1861, 1, '1: SIEM REAP - BATTAMBANG', '<p><span lang="EN-US">Transfer from Siem Reap to Battambang (approximately 3 hrs) with your English speaking Tour Guide. Arrive and check in to your hotel.&nbsp;</span>Lunch at a local restaurant.&nbsp;</p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">This afternoon head out of town to Phnom Sampeau. The limestone outcrop is home to a variety of temples and excellent views of the countryside dotted with palm trees and rice paddy fields. There is also a more sinister side as Phnom Sampeau is home to the Killing Caves, where Khmer Rouge executed prisoners.&nbsp;</span>Stay until dusk to catch the natural phenomenon of thousands of bats exiting a cave. They fly one by one out of the cave creating patterns in the sky. It is quite a spectacular to behold.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Meal included:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Lunch</p>\n<p>Accommodation at: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Selected hotel, Battambang</p>', 'BTB1.png'),
(1862, 1, '2: BATTAMBANG', '<p><span lang="EN-US">Spend the morning on a bike taking in the traditional Cambodian local industries surrounding Battambang. The private tour is guided by a local guide from a social enterprise initiative set up to provide scenic and informative bike rides through the local countryside.&nbsp;</span>Along the way you&rsquo;ll meet local families and learn about their traditional livelihoods and businesses, often unchanged throughout generations. Try your hand at local industries such as rice paper making, rice wine and snack on Battambang&rsquo;s famous bamboo rice cakes.</p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">In the afternoon travel a few kilometres to the start of one of the most fun &lsquo;train rides&rsquo; you will ever experience. The bamboo train or &lsquo;nori&rsquo; is consists of a wooden platform placed on 4 wheels and connected to a gasoline engine that powers the device.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Return to your hotel for the chance to freshen up before visiting a circus performance at the renowned Phare Ponleu Selpak. More in the style of Cirque du Soleil than a traditional European circus, be amazed for an hour by a show of modern Cambodian tales told through dance, acrobatics, aerial acts and music.&nbsp;<em>(Note: shows are held every Monday &amp; Thursday and occasionally on other days. It is possible to include the show on Day 1 if there is no show being held on this day)</em>.&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">After the show it is off the Jaan Bai restaurant for dinner <em>(Note: closed Mondays)</em></span><span lang="EN-US">. This training and development restaurant is run by the Cambodian Children&rsquo;s Trust which is working to break the cycle of poverty in Battambang by empowering underprivileged children.&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p>Meal included:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Breakfast &amp; Dinner</p>\n<p>Accommodation at: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;