e 3 Accent 5"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="49" Name="List Table 4 Accent 5"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="50" Name="List Table 5 Dark Accent 5"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="51"\n   Name="List Table 6 Colorful Accent 5"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="52"\n   Name="List Table 7 Colorful Accent 5"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="46"\n   Name="List Table 1 Light Accent 6"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="47" Name="List Table 2 Accent 6"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="48" Name="List Table 3 Accent 6"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="49" Name="List Table 4 Accent 6"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="50" Name="List Table 5 Dark Accent 6"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="51"\n   Name="List Table 6 Colorful Accent 6"/>\n  <w:LsdException Locked="false" Priority="52"\n   Name="List Table 7 Colorful Accent 6"/>\n </w:LatentStyles>\n</xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 10]>\n<style>\n /* Style Definitions */\n table.MsoNormalTable\n	{mso-style-name:"Table Normal";\n	mso-tstyle-rowband-size:0;\n	mso-tstyle-colband-size:0;\n	mso-style-noshow:yes;\n	mso-style-priority:99;\n	mso-style-parent:"";\n	mso-padding-alt:0in 5.4pt 0in 5.4pt;\n	mso-para-margin:0in;\n	mso-para-margin-bottom:.0001pt;\n	mso-pagination:widow-orphan;\n	font-size:12.0pt;\n	font-family:"Cambria","serif";\n	mso-ascii-font-family:Cambria;\n	mso-ascii-theme-font:minor-latin;\n	mso-hansi-font-family:Cambria;\n	mso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin;\n	mso-bidi-language:AR-SA;}\n</style>\n<![endif]--></p>\n<p>Today there is the chance to head away from the main temples and cycle through small villages and beautiful countryside. Friendly locals will wave and the village children will shout greetings at you as you cycle past.</p>\n<p>To avoid the city traffic head a little distance outside of Siem Reap and begin cycling. Pass Sra Srang, or the Pool of Absolutions, once reserved for the King and his consorts. You are now into the countryside as the road cuts through rice fields that are interesting to see year round, though at their emerald green best when the rice is being planted. Continue through local villages as you take the quiet, scenic route towards Banteay Srei temple.</p>\n<p>On arrival at Banteay Srei your cycling for the day will finish. However take time to explore the temple which unlike others is constructed of pink sandstone and the name means &lsquo;Citadel of the Women&rsquo;. Banteay Srei is one the best preserved temples in Cambodia with many exquisite carvings.</p>\n<p>Transfer back to Siem Reap by minivan. You should arrive in the early afternoon and the rest of the day is free to relax at your hotel or explore the town and its markets on your own accord.</p>\n<p>This evening enjoy dinner whilst watching a show of Apsara dancing, first performed in the court of kings at Angkor. Transfers to/from your hotel are without a guide and by way of a local remork (tuk tuk).</p>\n<p>A set menu of Khmer cuisine will be served as you enjoy the show.</p>\n<p>(Note: cycling distance approximately 35km on small roads and unpaved village sandy roads. There is time to stop for photos and the tour will last 5-6 hrs. The support vehicle will act as back up if you need to stop and to avoid traffic entering/leaving Siem Reap).</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'BIKE-ANGKOR-D2.jpg'),
(1820, 17, '8', '<p><span lang="EN-US">After a slow breakfast depart on a private tour to see the Tatai Waterfall. Taking the boat for about 45 minutes head into the heart of the Cardamom jungle&nbsp;until you reach the&nbsp;turbulent waters of the falls.&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">Depending on the season and water levels you can enjoy a natural hydromassage from the waters, kayak in the calmer waters and then enjoy a picnic lunch at the falls.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">In the mid-afternoon return by boat to the 4 Rivers lodge for your overnight stay.</span></p>\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span lang="EN-US">Dinner at the lodge.</span></p>', 'D8_edit.jpg'),
(1819, 17, '7', '<p><span lang="EN-US">This morning depart Phnom Penh as you head into the Cardamom Mountains for a stay at one of Cambodia&rsquo;s most unique places, the 4 Rivers Floating Lodge in Koh Kong. The drive will take about 5 hours from where it is a short shared boat ride to your accommodation for the night.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">On arrival you can check into your floating tent and relax a little. The tents are permanently moored up on a quiet stretch of river with the backdrop of rainforest. You will really feel at one with nature in your new home.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Activities available include swimming in the river, trying your hand at kayaking, fishing or in the evening to see fireflies lighting up a tree. It is also possible to go on an optional sunset cruise (paid locally).</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Dinner at the lodge.</span></p>', 'D7_edit.jpg'),
(1818, 17, '6', '<p><span lang="EN-US">Today there are a range of different options to suit families of different ages. </span></p>\n<p>(Optional: Apsara Arts Association -&nbsp;<span lang="EN-US">Be charmed by a visit to an NGO that helps to preserve a traditional Cambodian form of art, Aspara dancing. Apsara Arts Association works with students from poorer backgrounds to train them in the ancient art form that was performed in the court of kings at Angkor. This is a training school where you can watch the children of all ages practice their routines, hand gestures and dance in an informal setting. (Note: available Mon-Sat 0730-1030/1400-1700 hrs).&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">This activity could be more suited to younger children).</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">(Optional: Classic dance and/or Martial Art training -&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">Receive an initiation into either Classic Dance or Khmer Martial Arts at Selapak. An hour long private class by a teacher who has performed Apsara dancing for the late King Sihanouk or by a Yutakun Khom (Khmer martial art) teacher who is the son of the most famous master (kru) alive can both be provided. This is a sure way to get closer to Khmer arts that were once performed at the temples and are still alive today.&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">Classes can be active or passive to match the age/fitness of visitors though is likely to be more interesting for older children).</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">(Optional:&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">Half day cookery class -&nbsp;</span>Cooking can be fun for adults and children alike. Try your hand at an interactive class and learn about Khmer cuisine. Begin by visiting a local market by way of a remork, where your chef will guide you along the narrow alleyways and explain many of the ingredients required for your class. After return to the purpose built cookery school to learn how to prepare a 3 course Khmer menu. Finally it is time to try your own cooking for lunch. (Note - children from 8 years or older<span lang="EN-US">)</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">(Optional: Cambodia Living Arts show at the National Museum -&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">This evening attend a show in the grounds of the National Museum. Cambodia Living Arts support a programme that celebrates and cultivates the Cambodian arts community, empowering emerging arts professionals through their development and employment.&nbsp;Artists express the rich and vibrant culture of Cambodia through the traditional arts inspired by the time of Angkor. 3 dynamic and unique performances are offering on different days and all last for 1 hour).</span>&nbsp;</p>\n<div>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">(Optional: Souvanna Phum Shadow Puppet Theatre -&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">Attend a performance of traditional shadow puppets and sometimes, classical dance and drum shows at Souvanna Phum theatre. A 50 minute long show with a live Khmer orchestra will provide insight into traditional arts. After the show you can even try your hand at shadow puppetry. (Note Fri/Sat only)).</span></p>\n</div>', 'D6_edit.jpg'),
(1817, 17, '5', '<p><span lang="EN-US">Transfer to Siem Reap airport for your morning flight to Phnom Penh.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Upon arrival at Phnom Penh airport you will be met by our local English speaking Tour Guide and transferred to your hotel to check in (transfer time 30-45 mins depending on traffic).</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Phnom Penh was known as the &lsquo;Pearl of Asia&rsquo; and like much of Cambodia was a vibrant and culturally developed city until the 1960&rsquo;s.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">This afternoon take a traditional method of Phnom Penh transport, the cyclo, or three-wheeled pedal rickshaw to visit some of the sites. The cyclo is used by people to drop their children at school or to do their market shopping. However it is a fun way to get around short distances and see the city from a different angle. </span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">The first stop on the tour is at one of the most beautiful buildings in Cambodia, if not Asia. Central Market or Psar Thmei was originally constructed in 1937 following plans of the French architect, </span><span lang="EN-US">Louis Chauchon. In </span><span lang="EN-US">recent years the market has been restored with support of the French government. With a huge domed roof the art deco building holds four wings full of shops. There is something for everyone including souvenirs, clothes and food.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">The city of Phnom Penh is almost completely flat, except for a small hilltop known as Wat Phnom. This is the founding place of the city and a popular spot for Cambodians to come and pray for good luck. Stop to visit the pagoda and the gardens. Cool down with a fresh coconut juice.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">It is then on the short distance to the Riverside area of the city. Stop at the popular Blue Pumpkin caf&eacute; for some of the best ice cream in Phnom Penh.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">The last stop is at the port. Board a local wooden boat for a sunset cruise. On the hour long journey sail along the river with views of the riverside, the Royal Palace and the ever developing city behind. The cruise is a nice place to enjoy a quiet moment, some fresh air and reflect on your travels so far.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">After the cruise return to the hotel where the evening is at leisure or Travel Asia A La Carte can make arrangements for dinner at a local restaurant.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">(Optional: Dinner at Romdeng -&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">This evening dine at Romdeng, a non-profit restaurant run by Mith Samlanh, which has worked to build the futures of former street children and marginalized young people in Phnom Penh since 1994. Your visit helps sustain the project and importantly keeps the staff and their trainers away from the street and in gainful employment. Romdeng is set in a lovely colonial building with a nice garden for dining. The menu is ranges from almost forgotten recipes from the provinces to contemporary creative Cambodian cuisine. Deep-fried spider is also available for the experimental).</span><span lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>', 'D5_edit.jpg'),
(1816, 17, '4', '<p><span lang="EN-US">An exciting day awaits with exploring Beng Mealea temple where visitors can follow walkways and clamber over huge blocks a la Indiana Jones or explorers of old. This is followed by a boat trip to see the stilted homes on the banks of the Tonle Sap Lake which gives a real feel for life on the lake.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">After an early breakfast drive out of town to Beng Mealea, about one hour&rsquo;s drive from Siem Reap. Because of its location fewer tourists come here compared to the more popular ones located closer to Angkor Wat. Part of the mystique of Beng Mealea is that it has been left largely untouched. Nature has truly been left to its own devices &ndash; some parts have completely collapsed and jungle has grown over many parts. A wooden walkway provides a convenient path but there are plenty of opportunities to walk along hidden chambers and discover Apsara carvings amidst a jumble of blocks. &nbsp;</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Leaving Beng Mealea head to Tonle Sap Lake, the largest freshwater lake in Southeast Asia. The lake and its waters are the lifeblood of the country and millions of people depend on it. Officially a UNESCO Biosphere Reserve observing life on the lake makes for an interesting half day visit. Board a traditional wooden boat to visit Kompong Khleang, one of the lesser-visited villages on the lake. After reaching the village take a break to eat a packed lunch at one of the local houses. This will give you time to relax and watch as the villagers go about their daily business which is all on the lake. Following lunch continue by boat to see more of Kompong Khleang before returning to the boat pier and then onwards to Siem Reap.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">This evening you can choose to have a free evening or see some traditional dance.</span><span lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;</p>\n<div>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">(Optional: Apsara show -&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">This evening enjoy a show of Apsara dancing, first performed in the court of kings at Angkor. A set menu of Khmer cuisine will be served as you enjoy the show).</span></p>\n</div>', 'D4_edit.jpg');
INSERT INTO `itinerary` (`id`, `tour_id`, `day`, `description`, `image`) VALUES
(1815, 17, '3', '<p><span lang="EN-US">In the morning there is time at leisure or optional tours can be arranged.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">(Optional: Village Cycling Tour - S</span><span lang="EN-US">tart with a ride out along the Siem Reap river, then leave the tarmac and ride on small dirt paths through the scenic countryside and friendly villages where children will be welcoming you with a hello from every angle. You will see palm wine and sugar production, rice farming and all sorts of countryside activity that keeps the countryside. You can expect to return to Siem Reap around noon.&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">This ride is predominately on flat tracks and small roads - there are no hills in the area so anyone who can reasonably ride a bike can do this tour. There are sections on small dirt trails so the tour is not suitable for beginner riders.&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">A range of kids sized bikes, tag-alongs and child seats are available).</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">(Optional: Flight of the Gibbon -&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">Experience zip lining amongst the rainforest but just minutes away from the temples. With 10 zip lines, 4 elevated sky bridges and a 50ft abseil as a finale this is a fun excursion for people of all ages.&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">There is no a minimum age but there is a minimum height of 1 m (3 ft 3 in) tall to fit in the safety harness properly. Young children are often taken in tandem with a guide).</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">(Optional: Village Activity -&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">Depart the hotel after breakfast and drive to the Cambodian countryside to a real village and not one designed for tourists. There is the opportunity to experience village life and help in activities such as thatching, rice planting etc depending on the season. On arrival at the village take an ox cart ride until you reach the family who you will work alongside. Your activity could be transplanting rice, weaving wall panels, tree planting or making fish paste. None of it will be too strenuous and it will be a fun few hours. After take lunch with the family before a walk through the village with a stop at a community &lsquo;bottle building&rsquo; project. A donation will be put into the village fund on your behalf. Return to Siem Reap in the early afternoon.&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">The village activity is suitable for children of all ages).</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">In the mid-afternoon visit Angkor Wat, the largest religious building in the world. A magnificent moat surrounds the temple on all sides with a long causeway providing access. Take your time to look at some of the more than 3,000 Apsara or &lsquo;heavenly maidens&rsquo; carvings, all of which are different. The late afternoon light provides the best opportunity to observe and photograph the Apsaras.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Enjoy sunset at Angkor Wat with a cold coconut juice to cool down after your exciting exploration.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Later return to your hotel where the evening is at leisure.</span></p>', 'D3_edit.jpg'),
(1813, 17, '1: ARRIVAL SIEM REAP', '<p><span lang="EN-US">Upon arrival at Siem Reap airport this morning you will be met by our local English speaking Tour Guide and transferred the short distance to your hotel to check in. You will have the chance to settle in before some gentle sightseeing to start your visit to Cambodia.</span></p>\n<p>Travel this afternoon about 20 minutes out of Siem Reap to the Angkor Silk Farm. On a guided tour learn about all the processes from mulberry bush cultivation to the production of silk fabrics and accessories. During your visit, the guide will give you more details on the mulberry trees, silkworm farming, cocoon unwinding, preparation of the silk threads, tie-dyeing of the threads and silk weaving.</p>\n<p>Freshen up back at your hotel before dining at a local restaurant that supports a good cause. HAVEN is a training restaurant for vulnerable young adults from orphanages and safe shelters, as well as&nbsp;underprivileged young adults from very rural poor areas. By teaching them quality work skills as well as important life skills, these young people are supported in their transition from an institution to the real world as well as giving them a chance to step out of the poverty cycle.&nbsp;Dinner is a set Khmer menu.</p>', 'D1_edit.jpg'),
(1814, 17, '2', '<p><span lang="EN-US">This morning take a tour to see the favourite temples for children at Angkor. Travel in a fun way by remork (similar to the Thai tuk tuk) to walled city of Angkor Thom.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Proceed to Bayon Temple, which is located in the exact centre of the walled city of Angkor Thom. The temple is known for its many stone faces and towers that stare out to the jungle which once shrouded and hid the Bayon. There are some fun and fascinating photo opportunities here.</span></p>\n<p>After continue to Ta Prohm, a unique temple that has been left to nature with trees and vines growing amongst the structures. This is one of the most photogenic temples in the Angkor area and recently gained fame as the &lsquo;Tomb Raider&rsquo; temple after featuring in the Angelina Jolie movie. Enjoy walking along the sandy paths and under huge banyan trees as you explore this 12th century temple.</p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Return by remork to the hotel at midday where the afternoon is at leisure or you can choose an optional tour.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">(</span><span lang="EN-US">Optional: Afternoon village cookery class -&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">At midday head into the countryside a short distance outside of Siem Reap town. Transfer 10 minutes out of town by remork to a local village where you will try a hands-on cookery class. After an introduction to your chef it is time to take a walk through the village to visit a local family and see many of the ingredients being grown. Return to a purpose built bamboo pavilion where you will learn about Khmer cuisine as you cook at your individual work station surrounded by coconut and bamboo trees. A 3 course meal is prepared as part of the interactive lesson. Afterwards relax at a different pavilion perched over a fish pond as you enjoy your own cooking.&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">Return to the hotel after the class by remork where the rest of your afternoon is free).</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">(Optional: Quad Bike tour -&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">Experience the beauty of the Cambodian countryside with a 90 minute quad bike ride that with coincide with sunset. Fingers crossed that the weather is fine so you can catch a colourful sunset with the backdrop of rice fields.&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US">Children are welcome to sit with their parent as passengers, from 14 years old to 16 years old children can ride own quad only with an instructor as a pillion).</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">This evening enjoy some modern Khmer theatre at a performance of Phare, the Cambodian Circus by professional artists from Phare Ponleu Selpak. Originally a project set up in refugee camps as a way to encourage young people to express themselves using art, the Phare circus is slowly becoming a worldwide name. Tours have visited France, Germany and the UK already. Enjoy an hour long show which is a great, positive example of modern Cambodia and mixes theatre, dance, music, juggling and contortion.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">After return to your hotel.</span></p>', 'D2_edit.jpg'),
(1812, 18, '8: SIEM REAP - DEPARTURE', '<p class="MsoNormal"><span lang="EN-US">Transfer to the airport for your departure flight. &lsquo;Chum reap lear&rsquo; and goodbye to the Kingdom of Wonder. </span><em><span lang="EN-US">(based on morning departures)</span></em></p>', ''),
(1811, 18, '7: SIEM REAP', '<p><span lang="EN-US">This morning travel into the Cambodian countryside and out to the temple of Banteay Srei, dedicated to the Hindu god, Shiva. One of the most picturesque temples a morning visit provides a great opportunity to appreciate one of the most stunning achievements of Angkorian artisanship. Small in size the carvings are exquisite at one of the best preserved temples in Cambodia. Banteay Srei is different to the other temples as it is constructed of pink sandstone and the name means &lsquo;Citadel of the Women&rsquo;. </span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Visit the Landmine Museum located near Banteay Srei.&nbsp; The museum was founded by Mr Aki Ra who was once a child soldier for the Khmer Rouge before changing allegiance to work as a de-miner for first the Cambodian Army and later the United Nations. Aki Ra won an award from CNN as one of their Top 10 Heroes in 2010. Along with his Cambodian Self Help Demining group they have helped clear about 50,000 mines and weapons, many of which can be seen at the museum today.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Return to your hotel for a break around midday.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">During the 1960&rsquo;s and early 1970&rsquo;s Cambodia was culturally and artistically ahead of its neighbouring countries though as the Khmer Rouge took power much precious work and knowledge was lost. In modern Cambodia today there are many project helping to revive lost art, music and culture. Travel Asia A La Carte is proud to support these projects. One such example is Artisan d&rsquo;Angkor, a project established to support Cambodian arts and crafts. Visit the workshop this afternoon and see stone carvings, wooden sculptures, lacquer work and painting all being produced. Many of these can be purchased. A visit is a heartwarming reminder that progress in Cambodia can go hand in hand with traditional crafts.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">On the way back to your hotel a visit can also be made at Psar Chas, or &lsquo;Old Market&rsquo; in the centre of Siem Reap. The market has a fruit and vegetable section where many local restaurants and hotels will come to pick up goods. Also a tourist section has a wide selection of souvenirs.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">This evening enjoy some modern Khmer theatre at a performance of Phare, the Cambodian Circus by professional artists from Phare Ponleu Selpak</span><span lang="EN-US">.&nbsp;</span><span lang="EN-US"><span lang="EN-US">Originally a project set up in refugee camps as a way to encourage young people to express themselves using art, the Phare circus is slowly becoming a worldwide name and a good example of responsible tourism that has been a success story.</span></span><span lang="EN-US">&nbsp;Tours have visited Franc</span><span lang="EN-US">e, Germany and the UK already. Enjoy an hour long show which is a great, positive example of modern Cambodia and mixes theatre,&nbsp;dance, music, juggling and contortion.&nbsp;</span></p>', 'Phare_Circus_Siem_Reap.jpg'),
(1809, 18, '5: BATTAMBANG - SIEM REAP', '<p><span lang="EN-US">This morning transfer from Battambang to Siem Reap (approximately 3 hrs) and check in to your hotel. </span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">In the afternoon begin your exploration of the Angkorian temples by visiting the ancient city of Angkor Thom. Surrounded by walls with a height of 8m and length of 12km, the city was the last capital of the Khmer Empire. Five huge gates with huge stone faces provide access. Angkor Thom holds many important monuments which you will visit including the Bayon Temple located in the exact centre, the Baphoun, Terrace of the Elephants and Terrace of the Leper King. The most famous is the Bayon Temple which was once covered by dense jungle. Walking around the Bayon today you can wonder at the 54 towers all decorated with huge faces looking at every angle. The bas-reliefs are not as well-known as those at Angkor Wat, but are in fact more extensive with over a kilometre of detailed carvings featuring thousands of figures.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">After the afternoon exploring these fascinating temples return to your hotel to freshen up.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">This evening enjoy a dinner whilst watching a show of Apsara dancing, first performed in the court of kings at Angkor. A set menu of Khmer cuisine will be served as you enjoy the show.</span></p>', 'Angkor_Thom_face.jpg'),
(1810, 18, '6: SIEM REAP', '<p><span lang="EN-US">An early start today (approximately 5am) in time to catch sunrise at the largest religious building in the world. Leave the hotel by car and travel the 7km to Angkor Wat. Proceed into the temple and wait in front of the pond in order to get the best reflection as the sun rises behind the towers. This is the picture perfect image of the five towers reflecting in the waters as the sun appears. Built by Suryavarman II in the early 12th century as a state temple and later mausoleum, Angkor Wat was originally a Hindu complex to honour Vishnu, the Hindu God.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Instead of returning to your hotel take breakfast at Angkor Caf&eacute;. This allows you to reenter Angkor Wat before the tour buses arrive (most sunrise watchers return to the hotel to eat breakfast). An alternative eastern entrance is the best way to start a morning tour and avoid the crowds. Take your time to look at some of the more than 3,000 Apsara or &lsquo;heavenly maidens&rsquo; carvings, all of which are different. After this leisurely visit return to your hotel for some time to relax.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">This afternoon take a remork (similar to the Thai tuk tuk) to Ta Prohm, a unique temple that has been left to nature with trees and vines growing amongst the structures. This is one of the most photogenic temples in the Angkor area and recently gained fame as the &lsquo;Tomb Raider&rsquo; temple after featuring in the Angelina Jolie movie. Enjoy walking along the sandy paths and under huge banyan trees as you explore this 12th century temple.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Head to the South Gate of Angkor Thom board a hand crafted wooden boat or gondola for a romantic cruise on the moat surrounding the walled city. Relax as your boatman rows you to one corner of Angkor Thom. Ascend some steps and walk to a small but pretty temple. From there you can enjoy sunset over the Siem Reap countryside and avoid the crowds seen at many of the easily accessible temples.</span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span lang="EN-US">After this relaxing sunset return to your hotel where the evening is at leisure.&nbsp;</span></p>', 'Angkor_Wat_sunrise.jpg'),
(1807, 18, '3: PHNOM PENH - BATTAMBANG', '<p><span lang="EN-US">Leave Phnom Penh this morning after an early breakfast and depart in the direction of Battambang following the west side of the great Tonle Sap Lake.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">A short distance from the town of Kompong Chhnang and into the countryside one reaches the scenic pottery village of Ondong Rossey. It seems that every house is involved in the industry and all over Cambodia ox-carts can be seen selling wares from the village. Ondong Rossey is very typical of a Cambodian village and the surrounding countryside is beautiful with rice fields dotted with sugar palm trees. Keep your eyes out in case one of the village men are climbing up bamboo ladders to take the rice wine or toddy from the trees.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Board a simple local wooden boat to visit the floating villages at Kompong Luong. Absolutely everything is floating and this includes pig and fish farms, shops, a church and plenty of colourful homes. The community is a mixture of Cham Muslim and Vietnamese. The exact location varies according to the water level of Tonle Sap Lake and at times drifts a few kilometres to a new location.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Take a break for lunch at a local restaurant before continuing on to Battambang to arrive in the late afternoon (travel time 6 hours not including sightseeing or breaks).</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">The evening is at leisure in Battambang.&nbsp;</span></p>', 'Floating_village,_Tonle_Sap.jpg'),
(1808, 18, '4: BATTAMBANG', '<p><span lang="EN-US">Battambang is a charming town with the early 20th&nbsp;century French colonial architecture still prevalent and little modern development taking&nbsp;place. Arts and culture are being revitalized and galleries provide local artists the chance to present their work. Battambang is a slow-paced small town and provides easy access to friendly villages and the surrounding countryside&nbsp;where much of the sightseeing takes place. </span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Take a short walking tour to see some of the oldest streets and the Psar Nat market in central Battambang. The market was once bombed by the Khmer Rouge and today a local pizzeria stands at the site of the explosion. The narrow streets of the town have a lot of character and the buildings are better preserved than in most Cambodian cities.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Head a little out of town to one of the best preserved temples around Battambang, Wat Banan which is visited by climbing 358 stone steps to the top of a hill. Once a Buddhist temple, the origins of the temple are unclear though it could have been an inspiration for Angkor Wat to which it has many similarities. From the ruined temple there are nice views over the surrounding rice fields.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Travel to Prasat Phnom Banon Winery, Cambodia&rsquo;s only wine-making business. Whilst the wines won&rsquo;t be winning any international awards they are worth tasting. Also sample the organic ginger juice and perhaps the brandy. A short tour of the vineyard and facilities can also be done.&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Take a break back at your hotel before in the afternoon continuing with a fun activity again in the countryside surrounding the town.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">In the afternoon drive out of the small town to visit some of the local villages. Your guide can show you several of the different small industries &ndash; from drying fish to preparing tasty &lsquo;grolan&rsquo; (rice steamed in bamboo shoots) and the making of rice wine and rice cakes.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Travel a few kilometres to the start of one of the most fun &lsquo;train rides&rsquo; you will ever experience. The train or &lsquo;nori&rsquo; is consists of a wooden platform placed on 4 wheels and connected to a gasoline engine that powers the device. Used initially as a way of transporting goods between villages, today it is a popular way to transport tourists through the countryside with a little extra adrenalin added on a 12km trip.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">After this excitement return to your hotel where the evening is at leisure.</span></p>', 'Colonial_Battambang.jpg'),
(1805, 18, '1: ARRIVAL PHNOM PENH', '<p class="MsoNormal"><span lang="EN-US">Upon arrival at Phnom Penh airport/port this morning you will be met by our local English speaking Tour Guide and transferred to your hotel to check in (transfer time 30-45 mins depending on traffic). </span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">After the chance to freshen up it is time to visit a bustling market and one of the most beautiful buildings in Cambodia, if not Asia. Central Market or Psar Thmei was originally constructed in 1937 following plans of the French architect, </span><span lang="EN-US">Louis Chauchon. In </span><span lang="EN-US">recent years the market has been restored with support of the French government. With a huge domed roof the art deco building holds four wings full of shops. There is something for everyone including souvenirs, clothes and food.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">The city of Phnom Penh is almost completely flat, except for a small hilltop known as Wat Phnom. This is the founding place of the city and a popular spot for Cambodians to come and pray for good luck. Stop to visit the pagoda and the gardens.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Enjoy a relaxing Mekong River cruise seeing life and floating villages along the riverside before returning to the Tonle Sap River and cruising to the watch the sun setting over the Phnom Penh skyline. Cruises are on a shared basis on board a cruise boat with unique catamaran design to ensure a comfortable trip and last for 1&frac14; hours. Drinks can be purchased on board from the well-stocked bar.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">After return to your hotel where the evening is at leisure.</span></p>', 'Central_Market,_Phnom_Penh.jpg'),
(1806, 18, '2: PHNOM PENH', '<p><span lang="EN-US">This morning visit the Tuol Sleng Genocide Museum and the &lsquo;Killing Fields&rsquo; of Choeung Ek. During the Pol Pot regime, Toul Sleng, formerly a high school was converted to a detention centre known as S21. After interrogation and often torture, prisoners were transferred to &lsquo;Killing Fields&rsquo; where they were often tortured again and brutally killed.&nbsp; Choeung Ek was a Chinese Cemetery before it became the Khmer Rouge&rsquo;s best known Killing Field. The remains of almost 9,000 bodies have been excavated from mass graves in this area. Today Choeung Ek is a Memorial site for Cambodians and visitors from all over the world to pay their respects for those lost. A memorial stupa has been erected and displays over 5,000 human skulls, bones and clothes of the victims. During the Khmer Rouge years, thousands of Cambodians were tortured and imprisoned in detention centres around the country; the visit is a profoundly moving but also depressing experience. However the insight into the cruel Khmer Rouge regime is educational and part of understanding Khmer culture as it is today.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Take a break back at your hotel around midday.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">In the afternoon visit the National Museum, home to a collection of Khmer sculpture including many of the original pieces from the Angkorian temples. The four pavilions surround a beautiful garden where you can a short rest after exploring the museum.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">After explore The Royal Palace. Built in 1866 today the palace is home to King Norodom Sihamoni who has ruled Cambodia since October 2004. With its pagoda-style, ornate buildings the palace is an oasis of calm in a busy city. Wander through the complex, gardens and visit the interesting Silver Pagoda which houses a collection of Buddha statues, one of which is decorated with 9,584 diamonds and also take a look at the floor which is covered by 5,000 silver tiles.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Return to your hotel where the evening is at leisure. We are pleased to recommend some restaurants from Phnom Penh&rsquo;s developing food scene for you to explore.</span></p>', 'National_Museum,_Phnom_Penh.jpg'),
(2011, 20, '8: CRUISING THE MEKONG', '<p>This morning, embark by skiff to visit Koh Chen, or &lsquo;Chinese Island&rsquo; in Khmer. The inhabitants of this riverside village are renowned throughout the region as silver and coppersmiths. They purchase the precious metals in Phnom Penh and return here to make ornamental items such as the cups, boxes and delicately engraved tropical fruits used in Buddhist ceremonies and marriage blessings. Each family member carries out an aspect of these ancient methods and the intricate, beautiful workmanship belies its humble origins. Purchase whatever catches your eye before we continue on to the pagoda. If the monks are in residence, you will experience an authentic Buddhist blessing ceremony.</p>\n<p>Later in the day, continue exploring Khmer riverside life in the floating village of Kampong Chhnang, meaning Port of Pottery. Archaeological findings here link this now sleepy area as far back as the Dvaravati kingdom, dating to the 6th through 11th centuries when Kampong Chhnang was an important coastal stop on the trade route linking China and India. More recently, Cambodia&rsquo;s Prime Minister Hun Sen was born in this province. Colourful shrines with gilded Buddhas, villagers sporting conical hats more often associated with Vietnam and simple houses on bamboo stilts are among today&rsquo;s striking sights along the waterfront.</p>', 'Pottery_Village.jpg'),
(2009, 20, '6: CRUISING THE MEKONG', '<p>In the cooler morning time, cruise further south towards the Cambodian capital of Phnom Penh. Around 90 minutes into today&rsquo;s journey pause to head by skiff towards the shore for a visit to the intricately carved Prek Bongkong Pagoda with its upturned naga wingtips and angels appearing to hold up the pitched Khmer roof. This area is known for a series of &ldquo;silk islands&rdquo; along the river. We visit one of these villages where the weavers allow us to wander among their looms, admiring their skills at this knotty art form. Witness the entire process here, learning how silk starts with the worms, see silk thread being looped and dyed, then admire and purchase, if you wish, the final shimmering Khmer silk accessories.</p>\n<p>After return by skiff to the Aqua Mekong, ready to continue to the Vinh Xuong &ndash;Kaam Samnor border for the crossing into Cambodia. Guests who have opted for a visa on arrival should contact the Cruise Director for assistance with this process.</p>', 'Aqua_Mekong_New_Mekong_Cruise.jpg'),
(2008, 20, '5: CRUISING THE MEKONG', '<p>Leaving the Aqua Mekong behind, today journey by sampan into the Tra Su Cajuput Forest, floating deep into the acacia flooded forest under dense tree canopy. The 845 hectare preserve is a colony for 70 bird species including the rare painted stork and Oriental darter as well as bats, snakes and endangered turtles. Flora here is equally abundant with over 140 specified floral varieties including 22 tree varieties, 70 types of grasses, 13 species of aquatic plants, nine varieties of fruit trees and many medicinal herbs of great value in traditional Vietnamese medicine.</p>\n<p>Back on board the Aqua Mekong, sail onward to the village of Chau Doc, which sits along the H&acirc;u River, a tributary of the Mekong. You will head to the shore by skiff then by road for a change, about six kilometers to the 230m high Sam Mountain, the highest point in the Mekong Delta, and home to dozens of pagodas that dot the mountainside, some even set in caves.</p>\n<p>You will make the easy climb to the mountaintop for the most captivating views of the surrounding countryside&rsquo;s rice fields, and into Cambodia. But you won&rsquo;t be alone up here. As this is border territory, there is a military outpost on the summit. This legacy of the Khmer Rouge era confers a slightly anachronistic aura, which allows some insights into the tensions of that horrific period, although these soldiers appear far more relaxed. If you ask, they will likely pose for your photos, assuming you have a few cigarettes handy as payment for their impromptu modelling duties.</p>\n<p>Still at the top of Sam Mountain, Aqua Expeditions guests have the unique privilege to sit with the venerable Mahayana Buddhist monks at Long Son Tu Temple for a private audience. Enlightened, head back down at the foot of Sam Mountain, stopping to visit the Temple of Lady Xu, one of the major religious sites of the Mekong Delta. According to a legend, in the early 1800s, villagers found a statue of a lady dating to the 6th century in the forest. In 1820 they completed this temple, originally built of bamboo and leaves, to honour her and in hopes that she would bring them better crops, thus improve their lives. Even today, the marble statue of Ba Chua Xu, meaning "country lady" is worshipped, with Vietnamese coming year round to ask for her protection and benediction.</p>\n<p>The chef heads into the local market here with any gourmet minded guests interested to explore an authentic Vietnamese wet market, its copious baskets of the day&rsquo;s catch from the river, crisp vegetables and luscious tropical fruits.</p>', 'Chau_Doc.jpg'),
(2007, 20, '4: CRUISING THE MEKONG', '<p>Though you are in the heart of Vietnam, French colonial architecture stands all around&nbsp; today as you walk back in time with a tour on foot around Sa Dec town. You will roam around the fresh produce and exotic spices on sale at the local market and make your way to the colonial house once occupied by French writer Marguerite Duras. The house, built in late 19th century, is interesting in itself as a harmonious combination of Western and traditional Vietnamese architectural styles.</p>\n<p>Perhaps no one has done more to associate themselves with the Mekong Delta than Duras. Born in Gia-Dinh, as Saigon was formerly known, because her parents had responded to a campaign by the French government encouraging people to work in the colony, Duras&rsquo; early life here in Sac Dec was one of extreme hardship. Her father fell ill soon after the family arrived here and returned to France where h e died shortly thereafter. Her mother remained in Indochina with Marguerite and her two siblings, eking out a meagre living as a schoolteacher. It was here in Sa Dec that the teenaged Duras and Huynh Thuy Le, a rich Sa Dec merchant began their affair that Duras wrote about in her most famous work,&nbsp;The Lover.</p>\n<p>Your time travel continues after lunch on board the Aqua Mekong. You will cruise by skiff to a 40 square kilometre riverine island called Gieng Islet, to walk or cycle around this peaceful religious enclave on the Mekong Delta. Together visit Cu Lao Gieng Church, built in 1875 with materials imported from France. It is impossible not to admire its imposing bell tower that appears to pierce the sky high above its low-rise neighbours. At the Convent of the Providence Order and Catholic Church, interact with Sisters or the Father to learn of the religious influences on the surrounding communities, which you may visit to admire the indigenous pagodas and wooden houses built in the early twentieth century in traditional Vietnamese design and shaded by bonsai trees, as was the local custom.</p>', 'Deluxe_Cabin_Suites.jpg'),
(2004, 20, '1: ARRIVAL SAIGON', '<p>Upon arrival at Ho Chi Minh airport you will be met by our English speaking guide and transferred to your hotel (based on morning arrivals). Commonly called Saigon, the official name is Ho Chi Minh City, or HCMC.</p>\n<p>The afternoon city tour starts with Cholon, nestled only a few kilometers from the centre but distinguished from the rest of the city by its impressive Chinese influence. Discover the markets and shops of the area, and also the many pagodas and temples of Cholon.</p>\n<p>One of the most important temples for the locals is the Cantonese built Thien Hau Pagoda, dedicated to the goddess of the Sea; it attracts visitors from all over Asia. On the way back visit a lacquer ware factory, take a cyclo ride weaving through the bustling streets and catch a glimpse of Ho Chi Minh City''s everyday life.</p>\n<p>You may wish to stop and take a meal in a traditional Vietnamese restaurant (your own account) before continuing your tour to the War Museum and the former Presidential Palace.</p>\n<p>From the palace you will go on foot (your car will be available at all times) to visit the major sights of colonial Ho Chi Minh City including the Notre Dame Cathedral, Old Saigon Post Office, Dong Khoi Street (formerly Rue Catinat), the Continental Hotel, Opera House and City Hall.</p>\n<p>If you wish before heading back to your hotel, explore the trendy boutiques and shops, ask your guide for further details.</p>', 'Bustling_Saigon_market.jpg'),
(2005, 20, '2: SAIGON', '<p>Leave the hotel after breakfast for the hour long drive to Cu Chi, a suburban district of Ho Chi Minh city in Vietnam. It is famous for its Cu Chi tunnels, which were constructed during the Vietnam War, and served as headquarters for the Viet Cong. The tunnels of Cu Chi are an immense network of connecting underground tunnels. The tunnels were used by Viet Cong guerrillas as hiding spots during combat, as well as serving as communication and supply routes, hospitals, food and weapon caches and living quarters for numerous guerrilla fighters. The tunnel systems were of great importance to the Viet Cong in their resistance to American forces, through which they secured American withdrawal from Vietnam and ultimate military success.</p>\n<p>The 75-miles (121 km) - long complex of tunnels at Cu Chi has been preserved by the government and turned into a war memorial park. Some tunnels have been made larger to accommodate the larger size of Western tourists, while low-power lights have been installed in several of them to make traveling through them easier.</p>\n<p>Before visiting the tunnel, you will have a short time to watch a film showing how the tunnel was constructed. Then you will spend around 2 hours exploring part of tunnel system to gain a little understanding of what it liked during war time.</p>\n<p>Following the visit return to the hotel where the guide and driver will bid farewell leaving you for the rest of the day at leisure.&nbsp;</p>', 'Cu_Chi_Tunnels.jpg'),
(2006, 20, '3: SAIGON - BEGIN CRUISE', '<p>This morning meet the representatives of MS Aqua Mekong at the Park Hyatt Saigon. Your luggage will then be collected and taken directly to your suite. Board the air-conditioned bus for the scenic 1.5-hour countryside ride to My Tho where you will board the Aqua Mekong.</p>\n<p>Welcome to the laid back luxury of the Aqua Mekong. Settle into your elegantly appointed, river facing suite as the vessel begins to cruise and thus begins one of life&rsquo;s most memorable and photogenic adventures. Ascend to the Observation Deck if you wish, to take in the view of the swaying palms and bustling waterways of My Tho.</p>\n<p>Over the next seven nights, the Aqua Mekong sails along the one of the world&rsquo;s great rivers, the Mekong, towards remote natural and cultural destinations visited by only a few. First however, begin with a Safety Drill followed by a briefing on the Observation Deck in the air-conditioned Indoor Lounge with the cruise director and hear from the expert guides about your Mekong adventures ahead.</p>\n<p>You will start by going native, so to speak. People of the Mekong Delta rely on flat-bottom wooden boats called sampan to get around and transport goods to market. Climb aboard to paddle through Cai Be floating market, where more than 400 sampans gather every day, starting in earnest from 5 a.m. Each boat has one bamboo stick on the front to display that vendor&rsquo;s product, be it Vietnamese fish sauce, rice paper for dumplings, or colourful sweet confectionery. After continue your exploration of this area on foot or by bicycle for more up close glimpses of the daily life of Mekong Delta dwellers.</p>', 'Vietnam_Floating_Market.jpg'),
(2002, 21, '7: SIEM REAP', '<p><span lang="EN-AU">Today you will have a half day of visiting local art galleries and market and the rest at leisure. Please advise the guide the night before if you prefer a morning or afternoon tour.</span></p>\n<p>Take a short drive to the outside of Siem Reap to Theam&rsquo;s House, an atelier gallery of the Cambodian artist and designer, Lim Muy Theam. A refugee from the Khmer Rouge, Theam studied in France and returned home with a desire to preserve and redevelop Khmer crafts. The work is contemporary Khmer with smooth Buddha sculptures, brightly painted geckos and fish, lacquer boxes and paintings. Theam&rsquo;s employs only local villagers in order to support local communities and a visit is inspiring, as well as a good opportunity to purchase some modern crafts.</p>\n<p>Back in Siem Reap town visit&nbsp;Psar Chas, or &lsquo;Old Market&rsquo; in the centre of Siem Reap. The market has a fruit and vegetable section where many local restaurants and hotels will come to pick up goods. Also a tourist section has a wide selection of souvenirs.</p>\n<p>Last but not least visit two more galleries, that of the renowned designer Eric Raisana and of the photographer, John McDermott.</p>\n<p>Your last evening in Siem Reap is free to perhaps enjoy fine dining at the hotel or maybe head out to local restaurants such as Cuisine Wat Damnak, Chanrey Tree, Abacus or Palate Angkor. Siem Reap has a huge and diverse range of restaurants.</p>', 'Colourful_Old_Market_Siem_Reap.jpg'),
(2001, 21, '6: SIEM REAP', '<p><span lang="EN-AU">This morning travel into the Cambodian countryside and out to the temple of Banteay Srei, dedicated to the Hindu god, Shiva. Before reaching the temple </span><span lang="EN-US">visit the Landmine Museum located near Banteay Srei.&nbsp; The museum was founded by Mr Aki Ra who was once a child soldier for the Khmer Rouge before changing allegiance to work as a de-miner for first the Cambodian Army and later the United Nations. Aki Ra won an award from CNN as one of their Top 10 Heroes in 2010. Along with his Cambodian Self Help Demining group they have helped clear about 50,000 mines and weapons, many of which can be seen at the museum today.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-AU">Continue to Banteay Srei, one of the most picturesque temples where a morning visit provides a great opportunity to appreciate one of the most stunning achievements of Angkorian artisanship. Small in size the carvings are exquisite at one of the best preserved temples in Cambodia. Banteay Srei is different to the other temples as it is constructed of pink sandstone and the name means &lsquo;Citadel of the Women&rsquo;.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-AU">Following the visit head to </span>Golden Silk Pheach Farm is located 7km from the Banteay Srei temple and is an excellent example of an NGO that preserves traditional arts in a sustainable way that provides employment to local villagers in a poor part of Siem Reap province. More than 100 employees work to produce fine textiles using the rare golden silk with methods that have been handed down through the owners family. The work is extremely detailed, can take months to complete and many of the final pieces cost thousands of dollars. A visit is highly recommended for those who appreciate fine artisanship and Khmer culture. A tour of the silk farm lasts about one hour.</p>\n<p>Enjoy lunch at the silk farm &ndash; in the same way the silk designs have been handed down from generation to generation so have the family food recipes.</p>\n<p><span lang="EN-AU">After lunch return to your hotel where the rest of the day is at leisure.</span></p>', 'Golden_Silk_Farm.jpg'),
(2000, 21, '5: SIEM REAP', '<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"><span lang="EN-AU">In the morning continue your exploration of the Angkorian temples by visiting the ancient city of Angkor Thom. Surrounded by walls with a height of 8m and length of 12km, the city was the last capital of the Khmer Empire. Five huge gates with huge stone faces provide access. Angkor Thom holds many important monuments which you will visit including the Bayon Temple located in the exact centre, Built by Jayavarman VII, the Bayon Temple was once covered by dense jungle. Walking around the Bayon today you can wonder at the 54 towers all decorated with huge faces looking at every angle. The bas-reliefs are not as well-known as those at Angkor Wat, but are in fact more extensive with over a kilometre of detailed carvings featuring thousands of figures. </span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-AU">Visit other highlights of Angkor Thom including the Baphoun, Terrace of the Elephants and Terrace of the Leper King. &nbsp;</span></p>\n<p>Return to your hotel around midday. The afternoon is at leisure.</p>\n<p><span lang="EN-AU">This evening enjoy some modern Khmer theatre at a performance of Phare, the Cambodian Circus by professional artists from Phare Ponleu Selpak. Originally a project set up in refugee camps as a way to encourage young people to express themselves using art, the Phare circus is slowly becoming a worldwide name and a good example of responsible tourism that has been a success story. Tours have visited France, Germany and the UK already. Enjoy an hour long show which is a great, positive example of modern Cambodia and mixes theatre, dance, music, juggling and contortion.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-AU">Once the show has finished return to your hotel.</span></p>', 'Angkor_Thom_face.jpg'),
(1999, 21, '4: SIEM REAP', '<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"><span lang="EN-AU">This morning begin your exploration of the Temples of Angkor by visiting Angkor Wat, the largest religious building in the world. Travel there by remork (similar to the Thai tuk tuk).</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-AU">Built by Suryavarman II in the early 12th century as a state temple and later mausoleum, Angkor Wat was originally a Hindu complex to honour Vishnu, the Hindu God.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-AU">Angkor Wat is unlike other temples in that it is orientated towards the west, typically the direction of death. A magnificent moat surrounds the temple on all sides with a long causeway providing access. An alternative eastern entrance is the best way to start a morning tour and avoid the crowds. Take your time to look at some of the more than 3,000 Apsara or &lsquo;heavenly maidens&rsquo; carvings, all of which are different.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-AU">Continue to Ta Prohm, a unique temple that has been left to nature with trees and vines growing amongst the structures. This is one of the most photogenic temples in the Angkor area and recently gained fame as the &lsquo;Tomb Raider&rsquo; temple after featuring in the Angelina Jolie movie. Enjoy walking along the sandy paths and under huge banyan trees as you explore this 12th century temple.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-AU">Take a break around midday back at your hotel.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-AU">The afternoon is free at leisure to relax at your pool, perhaps take some spa treatment or explore the pleasant town of Siem Reap on your own accord.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">This evening enjoy Dinner whilst watching a show of Apsara dancing at your hotel, first performed in the court of kings at Angkor. </span><span lang="EN-US">(Note &ndash; if staying at Raffles the dinner is BBQ and held at the Apsara Terrace, if staying at Sofitel the dinner will be BBQ at The Royal Court during high season or buffet in The Citadel Restaurant during low season. If there is no show coinciding with Day 4 we will change to an alternative evening or propose another venue).&nbsp;</span></p>', 'Angkor_Wat_UNESCO_World_Heritage_Site.jpg'),
(1998, 21, '3: PHNOM PENH - SIEM REAP', '<p><span lang="EN-AU">After breakfast transfer to the airport for the short flight to Siem Reap (45 mins). Upon arrival at Siem Reap airport you will be met by our local English speaking Tour Guide and transferred the short distance to your hotel to check in.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-AU">Take the chance to freshen up </span><span lang="EN-AU">before in the afternoon travelling to Tonle Sap Lake, the largest freshwater lake in Southeast Asia. The lake and its waters are the lifeblood of the country and millions of people depend on it. Officially a UNESCO Biosphere Reserve observing life on the lake makes for an interesting half day visit. Board a traditional wooden boat to visit Kompong Khleang, one of the lesser-visited villages on the lake.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-AU">On your return to Siem Reap stop at Artisan d&rsquo;Angkor, a project established to support Cambodian arts and crafts. Visit the workshop and see stone carvings, wooden sculptures, lacquer work and painting all being produced.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-AU">The evening is at leisure.</span></p>', 'Life_on_Tonle_Sap_Lake.jpg'),
(1996, 21, '1: ARRIVAL PHNOM PENH', '<p><span lang="EN-AU">Upon arrival at Phnom Penh airport you will be met by our local English speaking Tour Guide and transferred to your hotel to check in (transfer time 30-45 mins depending on traffic). </span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-AU">Phnom Penh was known as the &lsquo;Pearl of Asia&rsquo; and like much of Cambodia was a vibrant and culturally developed city until the 1960&rsquo;s. Suffering at the hands of the Khmer Rouge the city was once evacuated by Pol Pot&rsquo;s army and became a ghost town. Today&rsquo;s Cambodia is a city on the move, still many years behind the development of neighbouring Vietnam or Thailand, though ever changing and one of the most interesting cities in Asia. Most visitors regret only having a day or two to visit the sites so make the most of your time in the Cambodian capital.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-AU">After freshening up take an original Cambodian method of transport for a tour of the capital. Taking a cyclo (pedicab) begin at the National Museum, home to a collection of Khmer sculpture including many of the original pieces from the Angkorian temples. The four pavilions surround a beautiful garden where you can a short rest after exploring the museum. </span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Continue to the Royal Palace. Built in 1866 today the palace is home to King Norodom Sihamoni who has ruled Cambodia since October 2004. With its pagoda-style, ornate buildings the palace is an oasis of calm in a busy city. Wander through the complex, gardens and visit the interesting Silver Pagoda which houses a collection of Buddha statues, one of which is decorated with 9,584 diamonds and also take a look at the floor which is covered by 5,000 silver tiles.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-AU">If time allows at the head in the late afternoon to the Riverside. This is a great place for people viewing. Take a short walk along one of the few pedestrianized walkways in Phnom Penh. See people exercising, practicing dance and just sitting and watching the action on the river.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-AU">Return to your hotel where the evening is at leisure.&nbsp;</span></p>', 'National_Museum,_Phnom_Penh.jpg'),
(1997, 21, '2: PHNOM PENH', '<p><span lang="EN-US">In the morning visit the Tuol Sleng Genocide Museum and the &lsquo;Killing Fields&rsquo; of Choeung Ek. During the Pol Pot regime, Toul Sleng, formerly a high school was converted to a detention centre known as S21. After interrogation and often torture, prisoners were transferred to &lsquo;Killing Fields&rsquo; where they were often tortured again and brutally killed.&nbsp; Choeung Ek was a Chinese Cemetery before it became the Khmer Rouge&rsquo;s best known Killing Field. The remains of almost 9,000 bodies have been excavated from mass graves in this area. Today Choeung Ek is a Memorial site for Cambodians and visitors from all over the world to pay their respects for those lost. A memorial stupa has been erected and displays over 5,000 human skulls, bones and clothes of the victims. During the Khmer Rouge years, thousands of Cambodians were tortured and imprisoned in detention centres around the country; the visit is a profoundly moving but also depressing experience. However the insight into the cruel Khmer Rouge regime is educational and part of understanding Khmer culture as it is today.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">Enjoy lunch at Romdeng, a non-profit restaurant run by Mith Samlanh, which has worked to build the futures of former street children and marginalized young people in Phnom Penh since 1994. Your visit helps sustain the project and importantly keeps the staff and their trainers away from the street and in gainful employment. Romdeng is set in a lovely colonial building with a nice garden for dining. The set menu is ranges from almost forgotten recipes from the provinces to contemporary creative Cambodian cuisine. (If you are still feeling hungry then deep-fried spider is also available for the experimental!) </span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-US">After it is time to visit a bustling market and one of the most beautiful buildings in Cambodia, if not Asia. Central Market or Psar Thmei was originally constructed in 1937 following plans of the French architect, </span><span lang="EN-US">Louis Chauchon. In </span><span lang="EN-US">recent years the market has been restored with support of the French government. With a huge domed roof the art deco building holds four wings full of shops. There is something for everyone including souvenirs, clothes and food.</span><span lang="EN-AU">&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-AU">After return to your hotel in the mid-afternoon where the rest of your day is at leisure.</span></p>\n<p><span lang="EN-AU">The evening is at leisure.</span></p>\n<p><em>Optional Evening Tour: Cambodian Living Arts show at the National Museum.</em></p>', 'Central_Market,_Phnom_Penh.jpg');

